some of the stories for myself! </ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>22 November 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>23 November 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>24 November 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>25 November 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>3 December 2010</DATE><ITEM>See research note! Hope you feel better Isobel. </ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>6 December 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>7 December 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>10 December 2010</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>11 February 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>15 February 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>24 February 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>25 February 2011</DATE><ITEM>EMH: I&apos;m satisfied with both docs at this point. I may be forgetting some of the finer points about attributes and dates. I will check any outstanding research notes next week. I spoke to Mariana about publication and I think we will proceed into the next cycle. Cheers. </ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>1 March 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c and rvc-c-equivalent</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>1 March 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="EMH" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>8 March 2011</DATE><ITEM>I added one extra fact, a new critical edition of Swamp Angel. 1 question about a bibcit for that.Also, there are a couple of researchnotes that I didn&apos;t quite understand and tried to respond to. Sorry for the confusion.Other than that, good to go.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>9 March 2011</DATE><ITEM>rev c equivalent to rbv c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>23 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>27 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>30 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MKD" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>1 June 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>3 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>Cas-ing and tag reports done but with some researchnotes that need answering. </ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>5 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub i</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>14 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>cfb c, cft c, pilot 41</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>21 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub c, pilot42</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY WORKSTATUS="PUB" RESP="MPO" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>23 June 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY></REVISIONDESC></ORLANDOHEADER><DIV0><HEADING>Writing</HEADING><STANDARD>Wilson, Ethel</STANDARD><AUTHORSUMMARY><SHORTPROSE><P>Born in South Africa and raised until age ten in Britain, <GENERICRANGE><NAME>Ethel Wilson</NAME> is best known as one of the first <TGENRE GENRENAME="REGIONAL"><SOCALLED>regional</SOCALLED></TGENRE> Canadian writers to capture in intimate detail the beauty of <PLACE><REGION>British Columbia</REGION>, <GEOG>Canada</GEOG></PLACE>. Her <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">short stories</TGENRE> and <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novels</TGENRE> were widely praised for her succinct and effective prose style, described by some critics as <SOCALLED>telegraphic</SOCALLED>.</GENERICRANGE> Despite her artistic achievements, Wilson was consistently modest in her claims about the value of her own work. Her scepticism concerning the value of national literature and creative writing classes produced some controversy in a time when the institution of <SOCALLED>Canadian literature</SOCALLED> struggled for articulation and recognition as a legitimate cultural form on both the national and international level.</P></SHORTPROSE></AUTHORSUMMARY><DIV1><HEADING>Youth</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PFIRSTLITERARYACTIVITY>Although EW did not begin writing until she was in her forties, she was a natural storyteller. <PMATERIALCONDITIONS>During walks at school in her adolescence, she entertained her friends by telling <TGENRE GENRENAME="FICTION">stories</TGENRE> in instalments.</PMATERIALCONDITIONS> In her late twenties, she once again told stories <SOCALLED>in serial</SOCALLED> to her younger cousins.</PFIRSTLITERARYACTIVITY> <PMATERIALCONDITIONS DISPLACEMENT="DISPLACEMENTYES">EW&apos;s experiences earlier in her childhood were important for her later writing. Her parents&apos; early deaths, that led to her displacement across three continents, seem to have influenced her work. While <TTHEMETOPIC>uncertainty</TTHEMETOPIC> plays an important thematic role, particular places and landscapes are in a sense <SOCALLED>fixed</SOCALLED> by EW&apos;s masterful descriptions. Furthermore, she often makes her fictional characters feel the need to establish a <TTHEMETOPIC>link with humanity in general</TTHEMETOPIC> since they are often deprived of close connections within their families, another theme that seems to reflect EW&apos;s early experiences.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 59" DBREF="64285">59</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 211" DBREF="64885">211</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMATERIALCONDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Early Writing and Short Stories</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>EW has stated that she wrote her first <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">stories</TGENRE> in the <DATE VALUE="1939--" CERTAINTY="BY">late 1930</DATE>&apos;s in her husband&apos;s car while he paid calls to patients.</PMATERIALCONDITIONS> <PATTITUDES><PMOTIVES MOTIVETYPE="SELF-IDENTIFIED">She did not write with the intent to publish and for most of her life considered her role as a housewife her primary occupation.</PMOTIVES> That is not to say she did not take writing seriously; she did, and this is partly what prevented her from attempting to write at an earlier age. Of her relationship to writing in her early years she said: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">there was only a subsoil of consciousness of the arts in the west . . . and I was frightened to take up a pencil &amp; <SOCALLED>write</SOCALLED>; it seemed an absurd thing to do, bumptious.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 79" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">79</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 93, 186" DBREF="64885">93, 186</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES></P><P>Accounts vary as to how EW&apos;s first serious publications came about. <PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="FAMILIAL">One is that in <DATE VALUE="1936--">1936</DATE> she showed three stories to <NAME>Reggie Tupper</NAME>, a friend with an appreciation for literature. He encouraged her to send the stories to the best periodicals at the time.</PINFLUENCESHER> <PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS>EW gave a different account: that she tried her hand at writing a few stories which she secretly sent out to publish without telling anyone.</PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS> <PATTITUDES>She said, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I had no standard of measuring whether it was impertinent to expect to be printed, and I didn&apos;t like to ask anyone.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 86" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">86</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 93" DBREF="64885">93</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES> <PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="FAMILIAL">The third account says that EW was encouraged to publish by <NAME>Sylvia Lynd</NAME>, a literary friend of her half-aunt <NAME>Margaret Bryant</NAME>.</PINFLUENCESHER> <PATTITUDES>All three accounts reinforce the <SOCALLED>amateur</SOCALLED> image EW had of herself as a writer. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 86-7" DBREF="64285">86-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>In the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">New Statesman</TITLE></HEADING><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="EMH" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1937-12-04">4 December 1937</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>EW&apos;s first <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">story</TGENRE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">I Just Love Dogs</TITLE>, was published in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="New Statesman">New Statesman and Nation</TITLE>.</PPERIODICALPUBLICATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 88" DBREF="64285">88</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PANTHOLOGIZATION>This story was reprinted in <DATE VALUE="1938--">1938</DATE> in <NAME STANDARD="O&apos;Brien, Edward Joseph Harrington">Edward J. O&apos;Brien</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Best British Short Stories of 1938</TITLE>.</PANTHOLOGIZATION> <PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>The same prestigious progressive literary journal published two more stories by EW: <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">I Have A Father In the Promised Land</TITLE> appeared on <DATE VALUE="1939-02-04">4 February 1939</DATE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Hurry, Hurry</TITLE> appeared on <DATE VALUE="1939-11-25">25 November 1939</DATE>.</PPERIODICALPUBLICATION> All three stories were eventually included in larger collections of EW&apos;s work. <RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: this information that they all appeared in larger collections of her work is not covered by the page numbers in the bibict. Is this okay?</RESEARCHNOTE><PATTITUDES><PPLACEOFPUBLICATION>Her decision to publish first in <PLACE><GEOG REG="UK">British</GEOG></PLACE> periodicals is perhaps indicative of her English heritage. Additionally, it possibly gestures toward her well-known suspicion about the value of <SOCALLED>Canadian literature</SOCALLED>.</PPLACEOFPUBLICATION></PATTITUDES><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 93" DBREF="64885">93</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 88, 96, 100-1" DBREF="64285">88, 96, 100-1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>While there is no evidence in the archives of any earlier attempts at publication, it is not certain that EW did not try to publish elsewhere, <PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS><RDESTRUCTIONOFWORK DESTROYEDBY="SELF">particularly in light of the fact that she often destroyed work that was rejected.</RDESTRUCTIONOFWORK></PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS></P></SCHOLARNOTE></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Hurry, Hurry</TITLE> is considered by some to be EW&apos;s most important publication out of this group of stories. <PANTHOLOGIZATION>It has been anthologized numerous times.</PANTHOLOGIZATION> <TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="DICTION">It is written in EW&apos;s characteristically precise and unsentimental language.</TTECHNIQUES> In it, <TPLOT>a woman walking her dogs is told to turn back by a man who claims there is a cougar on the path ahead. The narrator reveals what lies ahead is not a cougar, but the body of another woman that the man has <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="murder">murdered</TMOTIF>.</TPLOT></P><P>The story also illuminates EW&apos;s method of writing. She explained to <NAME>Robert Weaver</NAME> that she based it on actual events that happened in <PLACE><PLACENAME>Stanley Park</PLACENAME>, <SETTLEMENT REG="Vancouver">Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>, to a friend of hers twelve years earlier. She changed the location to path beside a dyke because she was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">only moderately fond of forests.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 97" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">97</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Drawing from experiences many years before a story&apos;s actual composition seems to have been EW&apos;s typical method of writing.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 96-7" DBREF="64285">96-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RDESTRUCTIONOFWORK DESTROYEDBY="SELF"><PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS>EW continued to send stories to the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="New Statesman">New Statesman and Nation</TITLE>; however, she destroyed those that were rejected</PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS> as well as those she felt were inadequate.</RDESTRUCTIONOFWORK><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 104" DBREF="64885">104</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>In Canada</HEADING><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PPLACEOFPUBLICATION><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>Although EW later claimed that during the war she stopped writing stories,</PMATERIALCONDITIONS> <PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>she nonetheless published two during these years, for the first time in <PLACE><GEOG REG="Canada">Canadian</GEOG></PLACE> publications. <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">On Nimpish Lake</TITLE> appeared in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Canadian Forum</TITLE> in <DATE VALUE="1942-07-">July 1942</DATE>. This story was solicited by the journal&apos;s editor <NAME>Earle Birney</NAME>, whom EW did not know at the time. <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">We Have to Sit Opposite</TITLE> appeared in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Chatelaine</TITLE> in <DATE VALUE="1945-05-">May 1945</DATE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 98" DBREF="64285">98</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="SLE Stouck 118" DBREF="65165">118</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PPERIODICALPUBLICATION></PPLACEOFPUBLICATION></P><P>On <DATE VALUE="1944-11-18">18 November 1944</DATE>, EW began corresponding with editors at the Canadian publishing company <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Company of Canada Ltd.">Macmillan</ORGNAME>. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">She sent Macmillan a bundle of stories, including the three published in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">New Statesman</TITLE>, proposing that the collection should be titled <SOCALLED>A <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> Notebook</SOCALLED> or <SOCALLED>Vancouver Child</SOCALLED>.</TSETTINGPLACE> <PATTITUDES>In her letters EW was characeristically humble: <RSELFDESCRIPTION><QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I send these, not with expectations of acceptance, but with plain humility, as I am not sure whether they are good, a little good, or no good, or whether they would interest a public at all.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="SLE Stouck 118" DBREF="65165">118</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> EW&apos;s deep uncertainty about the quality of her work is repeated in a letter sent two days later, on November 20, in which she calls the stories <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">trifling, old fashioned, and of personal interest only,</QUOTE></RSELFDESCRIPTION> and asks the editors to send the bundle back to her, assuring them that the she would <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">welcome them into obscurity again.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="SEL Stouck 119" DBREF="65165">119</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES> <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL">In these letters, EW also discloses that the American company <ORGNAME>Simon and Schuster</ORGNAME> proposed to publish a future novel by her. She explained to the editor at Macmillan that she had been in contact with the company since <DATE>1937</DATE>; however, there is no record of the original correspondence. <PATTITUDES>EW was uneasy about <ORGNAME>Simon and Schuster</ORGNAME>&apos;s proposition, especially in light of the war, writing, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I told them if ever I made a book I would remember, but did not commit myself. But now . . . <PATTITUDES>the bonds with home are too strong, and if I have any small talent at all I would prefer it to emerge as a product of home, or at least to remain British.</PATTITUDES></QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="SEL Stouck 116, 118-9, 122" DBREF="65165">116, 118-9, 122</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER></P><P><PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL"><NAME>Anne Blochin</NAME> of <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishers Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME> replied to EW&apos;s submission after one month. <TGENREISSUE>She wrote that in some of the <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">stories</TGENRE> EW had a <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> <SOCALLED>half-cooked</SOCALLED>, and added: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">If you cannot make something out of that <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Edgeworth, Topaz">Topaz</TCHARACTERNAME> saga you&apos;re not the writer I think you are.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 106" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">106</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> EW would rise to the challenge and revise the <SOCALLED>Topaz stories</SOCALLED> as what became <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Innocent Traveller</TITLE>. However, she put the project on hold some time and began working on a different novel, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Hetty Dorval</TITLE>.</TGENREISSUE></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 107-8" DBREF="64285">107-8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Hetty Dorval</TITLE></HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="65166" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Hetty Dorval, 1947"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="MPO" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1947-05-16">16 May 1947</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">EW published her first <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>,<TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Hetty Dorval</TITLE>, a <TGENRE GENRENAME="BILDUNGSROMAN">coming-of-age story</TGENRE> about a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">teenaged girl</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> mesmerized by the arrival of a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">glamorous, mysterious stranger</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> in the <PLACE><REGION REG="British Columbia">B.C.</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> interior.</TSETTINGPLACE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 127" DBREF="64285">127</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PATTITUDES>EW&apos;s desire to present herself as an amateur writer who published merely by chance has complicated determining her method of composing <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Hetty Dorval</TITLE>.</PATTITUDES> <PMATERIALCONDITIONS><PMOTIVES MOTIVETYPE="SELF-IDENTIFIED">In her talk <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">Somewhere Near the Truth</TITLE> given at the <ORGNAME STANDARD="University of British Columbia">UBC</ORGNAME> library, she claimed to have written this book as an outlet for anxiety at the time.</PMOTIVES> When <NAME STANDARD="Wilson, Wallace">Wallace</NAME> became president of the <ORGNAME>Canadian Medical Association</ORGNAME>, EW faced enormous social pressure and increased responsibility, as she agreed to organize women&apos;s functions at the annual convention. In the preface to a later edition, however, she claims that she wrote the novel during three weeks of rain while Wallace was away, after she had a dream about the bridge where the <PLACE><REGION REG="Fraser River">Fraser</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> and <PLACE><REGION REG="Thompson River">Thompson Rivers</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> meet in <PLACE><REGION>British Columbia</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>. She gives a third account in which the entire story came to her in a dream and she simply recorded it from memory. In any event, it is noteworthy that the novel was written very quickly, unlike most of EW&apos;s work.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 119-120" DBREF="64285">119-120</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMATERIALCONDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL"><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Hetty Dorval</TITLE>, set in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vancouver</SETTLEMENT>, <REGION>British Columbia</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>, and <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT>, <REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE>, draws upon EW&apos;s experiences at her Vancouver and Southport schools&mdash;<ORGNAME>Crofton House</ORGNAME> and <ORGNAME STANDARD="Trinity Hall School,, Southport">Trinity Hall</ORGNAME>, respectively&mdash;as well as her knowledge of the ranch country around <PLACE><PLACENAME>Nicola Valley</PLACENAME> in <SETTLEMENT>Merritt</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> and <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Lytton</SETTLEMENT>, <REGION>British Columbia</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>.</TSETTINGPLACE> <TPLOT>The narrative traces the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">allure and ultimate duplicity of <TCHARACTERNAME>Hetty Dorval</TCHARACTERNAME>, a glamorous new arrival</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> in town with a questionable past. <TVOICENARRATION>Hetty produces a profound effect on the schoolgirl narrator, <TCHARACTERNAME>Frankie Burnaby</TCHARACTERNAME>, as they continually run into one another, first when Frankie goes to boarding school in Vancouver, and again in London.</TVOICENARRATION></TPLOT> Although initially drawn to Hetty, Frankie is ultimately repelled by her when Hetty attempts to marry Frankie&apos;s love interest. At this point, we learn of Hetty&apos;s <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="illegitimacy">illegitimate birth</TMOTIF> and of her numerous <TTHEMETOPIC>affairs with powerful men</TTHEMETOPIC>. Ultimately, Hetty marries a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>wealthy German</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> instead of Frankie&apos;s young man, but whether she does this out of care for Frankie or for her own selfish motives is not clear.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 41, 59, 68, 120" DBREF="64285">41, 59, 68, 120</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Krim 16" DBREF="65265">16</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Pacey 45-6" DBREF="65266">45-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">The novel&apos;s epigraph is the especially popular passage from <NAME>John Donne</NAME>&apos;s Meditation 17 which begins <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">No man is an Island.</QUOTE> The epigraph illustrates the novel&apos;s critique of <TTHEMETOPIC>extreme individualism</TTHEMETOPIC> and <TTHEMETOPIC>selfishness</TTHEMETOPIC> embodied by Hetty.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Pacey 54-55" DBREF="65266">54-55</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL">EW was co-operative with her editors at <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishers Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME> concerning structural and narrative revisions, <TTONESTYLE>but was extremely stubborn on issues of style such as word choice, punctuation and spelling. She wanted to avoid as much as possible dots, dashes, exclamation and question marks, and over-use of commas. Some of these, she felt, were feminine; together they made prose appear too informal.</TTONESTYLE> <PAUTHORSHIP AUTHORNAMETYPE="PSEUDONYMOUS">EW additionally requested to publish under a different name, either <SOCALLED>Davida Bryan</SOCALLED> or <SOCALLED>Mary Millett Davis</SOCALLED>. <PATTITUDES>The request indicates that she felt uneasy about being generally known as a writer,</PATTITUDES> but she revealed a change of heart in a letter dated <DATE VALUE="1946-07-03">3 July 1946</DATE>. She wrote, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I discussed with myself and with my husband the name of the author, and decided to throw inhibitions to the winds, and be Ethel Wilson.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 123" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">123</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PAUTHORSHIP> Her second request was for a simple dust jacket consisting only of a map of Lytton country with her name printed in small letters.</PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER> The publishers compromised. <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>The original cover did not include a map, and EW&apos;s name appeared in large print. The design was, however, simple, with the title appearing in white on a green background.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 121-3" DBREF="64285">121-3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><PADVERTISING>EW was characteristically apprehensive about publicity. She strictly controlled the content of the publicity articles which appeared before the novel&apos;s publication. They included simply her account of the novel occurring to her in a dream, as well as her scepticism concerning the possibility of <SOCALLED>great</SOCALLED> Canadian literature (a view she would repeat throughout her life). A book launch was scheduled at the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishers Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME> company office in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG> </PLACE>.</PADVERTISING> Guests included fellow authors from Macmillan, Toronto bookseller <NAME>Roy Britnell</NAME>, <ORGNAME STANDARD="CBC">CBC</ORGNAME>&apos;s <NAME>Helen James</NAME> and <NAME>James R. Scott</NAME>, as well as reviewers from newspapers and magazines, notably <NAME>William Arthur Deacon</NAME> of the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Globe and Mail</TITLE>, an influential figure EW with whom would come into conflict with time and again.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 127" DBREF="64285">127</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">One typical critical response to <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Hetty Dorval</TITLE> can be found in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">New York Times Book Review</TITLE>. There <NAME>Seymour Krim</NAME> wrote: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">It has in it just enough solid merit to make its ultimate failure a matter of regret.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Krim 16" DBREF="65265">16</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Krim praised the writing, calling it <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">sharp-eyed and painstaking,</QUOTE> but argued that the story was an unsuccessful attempt at a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">morality play</QUOTE> and that relied too much upon <SOCALLED>telling</SOCALLED> as opposed to <SOCALLED>showing</SOCALLED>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Krim 16" DBREF="65265">16</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> A reviewer for the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Halifax Daily Star</TITLE> commented that the characters were not fully developed. This reviewer harshly continued: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">there seems no apparent reason for [the character&apos;s] story having been published.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 127" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">127</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The day after meeting EW at the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishers Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME> launch for the book, <NAME>William Arthur Deacon</NAME> of the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Globe and Mail</TITLE> published another negative review. In Deacon&apos;s opinion, both the first half of the story and the narrator are dull and there is not enough focus on Hetty, a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">far more vital centre of reader-interest than the gaping child.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 127-8" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">127-8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Another common criticism was that the story was melodramatic. <NAME>Claude Bissell</NAME> in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">University of Toronto Quarterly</TITLE> saw clear evidence of talent in EW&apos;s writing but claimed: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">To summarize the plot would be an injustice to <SIC>Miss Wilson</SIC> for its trite and melodramatic character merely obscures her real powers.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mitchell 11" DBREF="64825" QTDIN="QTDINYES">11</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Positive reviews praised EW&apos;s masterful description of the <TTHEMETOPIC><PLACE><REGION REG="British Columbia">B.C.</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> interior</TTHEMETOPIC>. A reviewer in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Chicago Sunday Tribune</TITLE> wrote: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Rarely in recent reading have I encountered an author who has transferred her love and understanding of a remote and beautiful countryside to paper with such skill.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 127" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">127</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Ottawa Evening Sun</TITLE><RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: This information appears to come from a note in the text which refers to a review in the Ottawa Evening Sun. Is this the same journal? I have added a bibcit below but I am not sure if the form is correct. img: acted on this note.</RESEARCHNOTE> compared EW to <NAME>Henry James</NAME> in her mastery of the psychology of her characters.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 127n36" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">127n36</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><TVOICENARRATION><NAME>Beverley Mitchell</NAME> argued that all of these reviews consistently failed to notice the <SOCALLED>unreliability</SOCALLED> of the narrator and the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">subtle complexities and ironies which this involves.</QUOTE></TVOICENARRATION><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mitchell 12" DBREF="64825">12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> For this reason, Mitchell claimed, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Hetty Dorval</TITLE> remains <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the most consistently misread and unappreciated of Wilson&apos;s works.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mitchell 12" DBREF="64825">12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PNONBOOKMEDIA><PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL">In <DATE VALUE="1947-07-" CERTAINTY="C">July 1947</DATE>, <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">John Gray</NAME> approached EW with the news that a Hollywood agent was interested in the rights for a film production of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Hetty Dorval</TITLE>. <PCONTRACT>According to her contract, the rights required EW&apos;s approval.</PCONTRACT> <PEARNINGS>Gray pushed for it, arguing it would help with the novel&apos;s sales as well as <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishers Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME>&apos;s profits overall. EW once again demonstrated a reluctance about the <SOCALLED>Americanization</SOCALLED> of her work, stating she would prefer an English production.</PEARNINGS> When a British company also showed interest, this led her to slow down the process of negotiations with the American agent. In <DATE VALUE="1947-11-">November 1947</DATE> the British company pulled away from the project, leading <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">Gray</NAME> to push EW for progress with the American agent. <PATTITUDES>However, EW replied that she felt strongly against it: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">My responsibilities are many, but I do wish to continue writing, with as clear and fresh a mind as possible. Cluttered up with Hollywood in this connection . . . . I would be defeated.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 129" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">129</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER> Requests for film rights would continue, but EW remained firm in her answer. <PPERFORMANCE>However, a radio dramatization through <ORGNAME>CBC</ORGNAME> was produced and aired on <DATE>15 February 1948</DATE>.</PPERFORMANCE></PNONBOOKMEDIA> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 128-9" DBREF="64285">128-9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><PEARNINGS><PCIRCULATION>Despite interest in adaptations of the novel, initial sales were very modest. <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Hetty Dorval</TITLE> sold less than one thousand copies in its first six months. Over EW&apos;s life time, however, it became her best-selling work.</PCIRCULATION></PEARNINGS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 129" DBREF="64285">129</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE><SHORTPROSE><P><PEDITIONS>The interest in a film adaptation nonetheless proved profitable in the end, since it eventually led <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Publishers Limited">Macmillan, London</ORGNAME>, to reconsider an English imprint of the novel. <PCONTRACT>In <DATE VALUE="1947-09-">September 1947</DATE>, a contract was signed for an English publication.</PCONTRACT> <PPLACEOFPUBLICATION>In <DATE VALUE="1948--">1948</DATE> the book appeared in <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE>, <PADVERTISING>preceded by advertisements consisting of a recommendation from <NAME>Sylvia Lynd</NAME>.</PADVERTISING></PPLACEOFPUBLICATION></PEDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The book was well received by reviewers at <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Punch</TITLE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">The Tatler</TITLE>. Noted novelist <NAME>Elizabeth Bowen</NAME> wrote that it was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">so remarkable as to convince me that its author should go a long way.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 128, 129" DBREF="64285">128,129</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Innocent Traveller</TITLE></HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="64328" PLACEHOLDER="EW, The Innocent Traveller, 1949"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="MPO" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1949-07-" CERTAINTY="C">Summer 1949</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EW&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Innocent Traveller</TITLE> was published by <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishers Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME> in London and <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>, a volume of <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">stories</TGENRE> which recreate a <TTHEMETOPIC>Victorian social order</TTHEMETOPIC>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 110-11" DBREF="64285">110-11</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PPLACEOFPUBLICATION><PEDITIONS>The book was produced in England but copies shipped to <PLACE><GEOG>Canada</GEOG></PLACE> bore a Canadian imprint.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 110" DBREF="64285">110</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEDITIONS></PPLACEOFPUBLICATION> <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL">Publication was delayed for some time. <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">Upon first receiving the manuscript in <DATE VALUE="1945-03-" CERTAINTY="ROUGHLYDATED">early 1945</DATE>, EW&apos;s editors at <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishers Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME> were divided. <TGENREISSUE><NAME>Anne Blochin</NAME> pushed for a more coherent narrative linking indiviual pieces, while <NAME>Margaret Blackstock</NAME> argued that the <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">stories</TGENRE> would <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">never make a straight <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 107" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">107</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TGENREISSUE></RRESPONSES> <PMATERIALCONDITIONS>The conflicting advice, Wallace&apos;s health problems, and a new editor at <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishers Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME> (<NAME>Ellen Elliot</NAME>) all prevented EW from moving forward with the project for some time.</PMATERIALCONDITIONS> It would take four years for the manuscript to be published. <PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS>In <DATE>1947</DATE>, she submitted the stories again  to both <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishers Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME> and <ORGNAME>Simon and Schuster</ORGNAME>, this time titled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Innocent Traveller, The">The Dancer</TITLE>.</PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME>Maria Leiper</NAME> at <ORGNAME>Simon and Schuster</ORGNAME> gave a positive response but overall the company was not satisfied. It and other companies saw no sales potential in the manuscript (partly because of its genre), while their readers specifically claimed that the content was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">fluttery and pallid,</QUOTE> lacking a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">solid skeleton</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 109" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">109</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PERSONAL">At <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishers Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME>, the new project was shuffled around while energy focused on promoting <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Hetty Dorval</TITLE>. <NAME>Ellen Elliot</NAME> eventually left the company and <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">John Gray</NAME>, who would become EW&apos;s intimate friend, took over her file.</PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER> <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL"><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">Readers at <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishers Ltd">Macmillan, Canada</ORGNAME>, admired EW&apos;s subtle irony and masterful use of tone, comparing her observational style to that of <NAME>Jane Austen</NAME>, but some continued to take issue with the problem of genre.</RRESPONSES></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER> Searching for direction, John Gray sent the manuscript to <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Publishers Limited">Macmillan</ORGNAME> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE>. <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The response was positive <TGENREISSUE>and the problem of genre was dismissed as inconsequential: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">This is not a <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE>, nor <TGENRE GENRENAME="BIOGRAPHY">biography</TGENRE>, nor <TGENRE GENRENAME="AUTOBIOGRAPHY">autobiography</TGENRE>, though something, probably, of each. That does not matter at all. . . . it is witty, delicious.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 109" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">109</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TGENREISSUE></RRESPONSES> <PCONTRACT>The London division of <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Publishers Limited">Macmillan</ORGNAME> offered Wilson a contract in <DATE VALUE="1947-09-">September 1947</DATE>.</PCONTRACT> <PEDITIONS><PPLACEOFPUBLICATION>It was eventually decided that <PPRESSRUN>1,500 copies would be a Canadian imprint,</PPRESSRUN> but that the book&apos;s production would be done wholly in <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE>.</PPLACEOFPUBLICATION></PEDITIONS></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 107-110" DBREF="64285">107-110</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER><PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY>During the publication process, EW sent numerous requests and revisions. She added three new chapters, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Recurring Pleasures</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Down at English Bay</TITLE>, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Family Prayer</TITLE>, which some consider to be the strongest in the text.</PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY> Proposed titles included <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Innocent Traveller, The">Prophane Dust</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Innocent Traveller, The">The Youngest Daughter</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Innocent Traveller, The">Journey to Vancouver of a Small Bird</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Innocent Traveller, The">Told in Vancouver</TITLE>, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Innocent Traveller, The">Vancouver Aunt</TITLE>.</PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER> The book was at last published in summer 1949 as <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Innocent Traveller</TITLE>, much to the delight of EW&apos;s family, who were pleased to see their family history preserved in literary form. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 110-1" DBREF="64285">110-1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TVOICENARRATION><TCHARACTERIZATION><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Innocent Traveller</TITLE> chronicles the <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">stories</TGENRE> of <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Edgeworth, Topaz">Aunt Topaz Edgeworth</TCHARACTERNAME>, who was based on EW&apos;s unmarried and revered great-aunt <NAME>Eliza Phillips Edge</NAME>.</TCHARACTERIZATION></TVOICENARRATION> <RSELFDESCRIPTION>Wilson always described it as a <SOCALLED>family chronicle</SOCALLED>, saying: <TCHARACTERIZATION><QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the persons and incidents are true, or, when I made some up (as I did), they are so truly characteristic of certain persons that they approximate to truth.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mitchel 27" DBREF="64825" QTDIN="QTDINYES">27</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TCHARACTERIZATION></RSELFDESCRIPTION> <TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST"><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS">In general, the stories cover the family&apos;s <TTHEMETOPIC>move from <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE> to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC> in the Victorian period,</TSETTINGPLACE></TSETTINGDATE> but the focus is on Topaz, who possesses a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">sharp wit and zest for life. However, her life perspective is narrow</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> and she has little perception of the world beyond her family. She is selfish and isolated in her protected privilege and is compared to a water-glider, experiencing neither <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">acute sorrow or acute joy or dull despair.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mitchell 29" DBREF="64825" QTDIN="QTDINYES">29</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Local reviews of the book in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> were generally positive. The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Vancouver Sun</TITLE> claimed to see development in EW&apos;s writing, asserting (despite the fact that <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Innocent Traveller</TITLE> was mostly written before <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Hetty Dorval</TITLE>) that she had <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">acquired a polish and lustre just glimpsed in her first effort.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mitchell 12" DBREF="64825" QTDIN="QTDINYES">12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Throughout Canada reviews were also positive. The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Saturday Review</TITLE> described the book as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">gentle, engaging, quietly wise, and nostalgic without being dated.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mitchell 12" DBREF="64825" QTDIN="QTDINYES">12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Toronto Star</TITLE>&apos;s reviewer claimed that the book was so full of pleasurable passages that its pages could be enjoyable even if read at random. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 111" DBREF="64285">111</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Negative reviews seemed to repeat <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishers Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME>&apos;s original worry that the collection was <SOCALLED>half-cooked</SOCALLED>. Aunt Topaz was characterized by the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Canadian Forum</TITLE> as a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">terrible bore</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, whom the reviewer found <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">almost as tiresome to the reader as it must have been to her.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mitchell 12" DBREF="64825" QTDIN="QTDINYES">12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <NAME>William Arthur Deacon</NAME>, the most important Canadian book reviewer at the time, once again severely criticized the work, taking issue with the <SOCALLED>dull</SOCALLED> material in the part set in England and the overall lack of formal structure and purpose. He wrote: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">A novel should involve some working out of human destiny. . . . [Topaz&apos;s story] never came near the dignity of tragedy. . . . she made no impress on anything or anybody . . . . she maintained her own integrity at zero.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 111-112" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">111-112</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <TCHARACTERIZATION>Deacon took issue with specific characters,</TCHARACTERIZATION> <RSELFDESCRIPTION>whom EW went on to defend in a letter to <NAME>Frank Upjohn</NAME>, the vice-president of <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada">Macmillan</ORGNAME> at the time. In the letter, she takes care to note she is <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">defending my <SOCALLED>characters,</SOCALLED> not myself.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="SEL Stouck 155" DBREF="65165">155</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> However, she was embarrassed by Deacon&apos;s review, which she perceived as an attack on her family as well as her writing.</RSELFDESCRIPTION> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">A second disappointing review appeared in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> in <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE> where EW had relatives, <PATTITUDES>once again stirring up a sense of embarrassment.</PATTITUDES> This review maintained that <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Edgeworth, Topaz">Aunt Topaz</TCHARACTERNAME> fails to charm and that the secondary characters fail to <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">come to life.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 112-13" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">112-13</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> On <DATE VALUE="1949-12-17">17 December 1949</DATE> a review in the <PLACE><GEOG REG="USA">U.S.</GEOG></PLACE> <ORGNAME STANDARD="Roman Catholic Church">Catholic</ORGNAME> publication <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">America</TITLE> called the work <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">an English sort of book, as un-American as can be,</QUOTE> an <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">excellent example of what <NAME STANDARD="Shaw, George Bernard">Bernard Shaw</NAME> meant when he said that the Americans and the English were two like people who were divided by a common language.</QUOTE> This reviewer identified in particular the scene where <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Edgeworth, Topaz">Aunt Topaz</TCHARACTERNAME> <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">curtseys to the pictures of the King and Queen that are displayed in the lobby of a Canadian hotel, in order to impress the American tourists and to demonstrate her own loyalty.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Ready, America 82 (17 December 1949): 352" DBREF="68005">82 (17 December 1949): 352</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Nonetheless, the reviewer went on to praise EW&apos;s writing, drawing a comparison with <NAME>Jane Austen</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Barrie, Sir J. M.">James Barrie</NAME>.</RRESPONSES></P><P><RSELFDESCRIPTION>EW continued to defend <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Innocent Traveller</TITLE> throughout her life. In letters to friends she wrote that she had a special love for it as an accurate portrayal of her life growing up with her aunts. <TGENREISSUE>She also felt that it was an important piece of <TGENRE GENRENAME="HISTORY">social history</TGENRE>, documenting the <TTHEMETOPIC>travel of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a middleclass English family arriving [in Canada], ideas, prejudgments &amp; all,</QUOTE></TTHEMETOPIC> and argued that such families had made <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a terrific contribution</QUOTE> to Vancouver society.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 113" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">113</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TGENREISSUE></RSELFDESCRIPTION></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Later critics concede that the work has value despite the apparent vapidity of the <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Edgeworth, Topaz">Aunt Topaz</TCHARACTERNAME> character. <NAME>William H. New</NAME> has argued <TCHARACTERIZATION>that her lack of depth helps illustrate her anachronistic function, which reveals the contingency of social values in general.</TCHARACTERIZATION> The work is treated very differently by <NAME>Arnold H. Itwaru</NAME>, who focuses on the way characters in the text repeatedly subordinate non-whites. He uses as example Aunt Topaz&apos;s treatment of the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>black porter</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> she encounters in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Montreal</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Quebec"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>, whom she treats like an exotic species of animal, as well as the suspicion with which <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Chinese servants</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> are treated both by other characters and by the narrator. He cites a particularly problematic scene in which the servant <TCHARACTERNAME>Fooey</TCHARACTERNAME> is praying; the narrator describes his prayers as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">thinking in Chinese of God knows what.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 115" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">115</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <NAME>Irene Howard</NAME> views the novel as emblematic of EW&apos;s description of the two <SOCALLED>types</SOCALLED> of <ORGNAME STANDARD="Methodist Church">Methodists</ORGNAME> in her family: the strict and shockable Malkins of her mother&apos;s side and the unstrict and unshockable Bryants of her father&apos;s side.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 114-115" DBREF="64285">114-115</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Howard" DBREF="65345"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PEDITIONS><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Innocent Traveller</TITLE> was reprinted in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> and <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> in <DATE VALUE="1960--">1960</DATE>. <PCIRCULATION>It sold steadily but went out of print in 1970.</PCIRCULATION> In <DATE VALUE="1982--">1982</DATE> it was included in <ORGNAME>McClelland and Stewart</ORGNAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">New Canadian Library</TITLE> series; this edition was reissued in <DATE VALUE="1990--">1990</DATE>. The reissue included an afterword by <NAME>P. K. Page</NAME> and the cover depicted <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Lighthouse at Prospect Point</TITLE>, a painting by <NAME>E. J. Hughes</NAME>. <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL">In the afterword, <NAME STANDARD="Page, P. K.">Page</NAME> writes that <TCHARACTERIZATION>despite her vapidity, Aunt Topaz is extraordinary and memorable, owing to the fact that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Wilson&apos;s inscribing eye&mdash;her incising, incisive eye&mdash;is sufficiently infused with a loving spirit that we catch her love.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 117, 118" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">117,118</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TCHARACTERIZATION></RRESPONSES></PEDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Equations of Love</TITLE></HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="64330" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Equations of Love, 1952"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="MPO" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE VALUE="1952-03-" CERTAINTY="BY">March 1952</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EW published her two <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVELLA">novellas</TGENRE> which together are titled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Equations of Love</TITLE>, through <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishers Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME> of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 148" DBREF="64285">148</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PMATERIALCONDITIONS><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Equations of Love</TITLE>, consisting of <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Lilly&apos;s Story</TITLE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Tuesday and Wednesday</TITLE>, appeared after <NAME>Wallace Wilson</NAME>&apos;s prolonged and life-threatening illness.</PMATERIALCONDITIONS></P><P>EW began work on <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Tuesday and Wednesday</TITLE> two years before <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Equations of Love</TITLE> was published. She sent <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">John Gray</NAME> part of the manuscript on <DATE VALUE="1948-03-21">21 March 1948</DATE>. Shortly afterward, Wallace became extremely ill. <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">In a letter sent with this draft, EW tentatively titles the work <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Equations of Love, The">Wilderness of Monkeys</TITLE> after Shylock&apos;s phrase in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Merchant of Venice</TITLE> about his daughter&apos;s acquiring a monkey as a swap for a ring given him by his dead wife.</TINTERTEXTUALITY> <RSELFDESCRIPTION>She mentions that the story <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">has been brewing for some time</QUOTE> but that it has also <TCHARACTERIZATION><QUOTE DIRECT="Y">moved out of my control and I can&apos;t change its course. You will say where is it going. . . . I have to write about <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Tritt, Victoria May">Victoria</TCHARACTERNAME>&mdash;nebulous though she is&mdash;because to my surprise she is the linch-pin of the story.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="SEL Stouck 145-6" DBREF="65165">145-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TCHARACTERIZATION> She further describes the story as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><EMPH>definitely</EMPH> Canadian</QUOTE>, something quite curious for EW who consistently stated that writers should not attempt to produce <SOCALLED>Canadian</SOCALLED> fiction, but should simply write well.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="SEL Stouck 146" DBREF="65165" QTDIN="QTDINYES">146</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RSELFDESCRIPTION> <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL">Two months later, when EW had not heard back from <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">Gray</NAME>, she asked for the manuscript back. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 144" DBREF="64285">144</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Gray had two readers&apos; reports of the story and both were very critical. The first reader disliked what he felt to be the author&apos;s superior attitude to her characters, annoyingly disguised as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">supreme tolerance</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 145" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">145</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The second reader felt that the novella lacked structure and that the style was too meandering. <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">Gray</NAME> further commented that EW&apos;s authorial narration was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">dominating her characters too much.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 145" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">145</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER> Because of Wallace&apos;s illness, EW put the story aside for some time.</P><P><TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Lilly&apos;s Story</TITLE> emerged out of the loose ends of sub-plots from <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Innocent Traveller</TITLE>. <TCHARACTERNAME>Yow</TCHARACTERNAME>, the Hastings&apos; <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Chinese servant</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> from the earlier work, had a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>white lady friend</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who <SOCALLED>made other connections</SOCALLED> when Yow went to <TTHEMETOPIC>jail for stealing</TTHEMETOPIC> from the Hastings family. Originally titled <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Lilly&apos;s Story">The Journey of a White Lady Friend</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Lilly&apos;s Story</TITLE> traces these connections.</P><RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: should this have a bibcit here to cover the information about the original title?</RESEARCHNOTE><P>EW sent <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">John Gray</NAME> the first two chapters of this story and an outline in <DATE VALUE="1950-07-">July 1950</DATE>. The published story remained true to the outine with the exception of one significant detail in which <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Waller, Eleanor">Eleanor</TCHARACTERNAME>, <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Waller, Lilly">Lilly</TCHARACTERNAME>&apos;s daughter, marries into Vancouver society but <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="illegitimacy">gives birth to a Chinese baby</TMOTIF>, thus apparently <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="reputation, women&apos;s">destroying <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Lilly Waller">Lilly</TCHARACTERNAME>&apos;s attempt to secure acceptance and respectability for her family</TMOTIF>. The dramatic moment was left out because the idea that <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Eleanor Waller">Eleanor</TCHARACTERNAME> had entirely recessive genes which suddenly appeared as dominant in her child was not considered biologically realistic. In the <DATE VALUE="1950-10--" CERTAINTY="C">autumn of 1950</DATE>, EW&apos;s husband, Wallace, want so far as to consult his friends in the medical community on the matter.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 147" DBREF="64285">147</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The original plot is revealing in many ways. It is consistent with what EW described in a letter to Gray as the essence of both stories, characterizing them as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">studies in <TTHEMETOPIC>self-deception and lies</TTHEMETOPIC>. . . . <TTHEMETOPIC>Truth</TTHEMETOPIC> is sometimes absolute, but very often a relative matter, as we know, yet frighteningly unethical (because the lies win) but so is life, very often.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 148" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">148</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Instead of ending with an illusion-shattering revelation, EW decided to end the story differently, with Eleanor leading a happy life and Lilly getting married to Mr Sprockett.</P><P><PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL"><PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS>EW sent Gray a polished version of <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Tuesday and Wednesday</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Lilly&apos;s Story">The Journey of a White Lady Friend</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">Mr Sleepwalker</TITLE>, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">The Cut Off</TITLE> in <DATE>July 1950</DATE>. Readers at <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishers Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME> found promise in <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Lilly&apos;s Story">The Journey of a White Lady Friend</TITLE> and found <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Tuesday and Wednesday</TITLE> to be publishable in its polished form.</PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS> <TGENREISSUE>The <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">stories</TGENRE>, however, were <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVELLA">novella</TGENRE> length, leading to some confusion concerning how they should be published. EW suggested they be published separately, but <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">Gray</NAME> thought it best to put them together.</TGENREISSUE> <TVOICENARRATION>Nonetheless, Gray tried to persuade EW to change the tone of her narration and remove <SOCALLED>intrusions</SOCALLED> such as authorial asides.</TVOICENARRATION> EW eventually conceded and made some revisions. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 145-6 " DBREF="64285">145-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TCHARACTERIZATION><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE">Characters in both narratives are from the east end of Vancouver, an area EW would not have known well</TSETTINGPLACE> (although she could recall experiences at the <PLACE><PLACENAME>Langham Hotel </PLACENAME><SETTLEMENT REG="Vancouver"></SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> boarding house) and came from a lower social class than she usually wrote of.</TCHARACTERIZATION> EW&apos;s later fiction increasingly focuses on <TTHEMETOPIC>women in a state of personal crisis</TTHEMETOPIC>.<TPLOT><TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Tuesday and Wednesday</TITLE> presents a realistic portrayal of two days in the life of a <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="unhappy marriage">dysfunctional couple</TMOTIF>, <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Johnson, Myrtle">Myrtle Johnson</TCHARACTERNAME> and <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Johnson, Mort">Mortimer <SOCALLED>Mort</SOCALLED> Johnson</TCHARACTERNAME>. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE">The story primarily takes place in depressing scenes: drab and dingy boarding houses and rooms, or on the streets amidst dreary, wet weather.</TSETTINGPLACE> Myrtle controls others by playing <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">the eternal victim</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, thereby manipulating them into feeling sorry for her. EW characterizes her as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a complete mistress (or victim) of the volte-face, of the turn-about.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Pacey 104" DBREF="65266" QTDIN="QTDINYES">104</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <TCHARACTERIZATION>Mort is a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="MALE">labourer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, self-conscious about his position in life, who dies suddenly in the company of his friend <TCHARACTERNAME>Eddie Hansen</TCHARACTERNAME>. He is an ambivalent character: a combination of depravity, irritability and gentleness, capable of sometimes considering others but also prone to sloth and selfishness.</TCHARACTERIZATION> Myrtle believes he died because he was drunk, thereby disgracing her. But her husband&apos;s reputation is saved by Myrtle&apos;s <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>unmarried, lonely, and timid cousin</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> <TCHARACTERNAME>Victoria May Tritt</TCHARACTERNAME> who sees Mort shortly before his death and inventively insists that he died in an act of heroism, <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="rescue">attempting to save his friend from drowning</TMOTIF>.</TPLOT> <TCHARACTERNAME>Mrs Emblem</TCHARACTERNAME>, Myrtle&apos;s aunt, can be seen as the foil for the mousy Victoria May. <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Outgoing and flamboyant</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, she thoroughly enjoys the sensual pleasures in life. <TCHARACTERIZATION>Most characters undergo a kind of transformation: Myrtle becomes more self-assured and confident and less inclined to manipulate, Mort is depicted as hero after his death and Victoria May becomes less timid when she confidently asserts that Mort died a hero. </TCHARACTERIZATION><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Keith" DBREF="65346"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Lannert" DBREF="65347"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Pacey 98" DBREF="65266">98</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 144" DBREF="64285">144</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><RESEARCHNOTE>EMH: This is from the Oxford Companion to Canadian Literature which I accessed online. I tried to add the bibliography entry. I put in info for a monographic entry, but cited it as Web_Site. I supposed that I could have just cited the actual book, as I had enough information. But I would rather cite the web source (even though access is restricted as I noted in the scholar note). Same thing goes for the Lannert. img: I think you&apos;ve done well here, but will leave note for Mariana in case. mpo: also think this is ok, revised the bibl entry and it is good to go now.</RESEARCHNOTE></P><P><TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Lilly&apos;s Story</TITLE> uses a precise linearity to chart the gains and losses of a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>single mother</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>&apos;s <TMOTIF>quest</TMOTIF> for <TTHEMETOPIC>bourgeois respectability</TTHEMETOPIC>. <TPLOT>The story takes place over the course of thirty to forty years. <TCHARACTERNAME>Lilly Waller</TCHARACTERNAME> is born to irresponsible, alcoholic parents. She runs away and becomes a waitress but is seduced by <TCHARACTERIZATION>Yow</TCHARACTERIZATION> (the same <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Chinese servant</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> of the Hastings family who featured in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Innocent Traveller</TITLE>). She eventually runs off again and lives with a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>Welsh miner</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, becomes pregnant and gives birth to a daughter, <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Waller, Eleanor">Eleanor</TCHARACTERNAME>. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE">Lilly works various jobs throughout Canada before eventually marrying an elderly widower from <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Winnipeg</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Manitoba"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>.</TSETTINGPLACE></TPLOT> <TCHARACTERIZATION>The story is primarily driven by the development of Lilly&apos;s character. Although originally irresponsible, Lilly becomes <TTHEMETOPIC>determined to improve her life</TTHEMETOPIC> and especially her daughter&apos;s life.</TCHARACTERIZATION> The story is also driven by the theme of the <TTHEMETOPIC>transformative power of unconditional love</TTHEMETOPIC>, particularly in conditions that are frightening and difficult.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Pacey 119" DBREF="65266">119</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">The two stories share an epigraph from <NAME>Charles Dickens</NAME>&apos; <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Bleak House</TITLE>: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><QUOTE DIRECT="N">Now, my young friends,</QUOTE> [said Mr. Chadband] <QUOTE DIRECT="N">what is this Terewth. . . firstly (in a spirit of love) what is the common sort of Terewth. . . .</QUOTE></QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Pacey 97" DBREF="65266" QTDIN="QTDINYES">97</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The epigraph gestures toward the ambiguity concerning morality and judgment demonstrated in the text. In both stories, lies are told without hesitation or compunction.</TINTERTEXTUALITY> The characters in each are portrayed with some complexity and the reader&apos;s first impression of superficial, trivial lives gives way to sympathy or respect.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Pacey 98-99" DBREF="65266">98-99</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The Canadian reviews of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Equations of Love</TITLE> were mixed. EW finally won over the reviewer at the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Globe and Mail</TITLE> (it was not, this time, <NAME>William Arthur Deacon</NAME>). <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Vancouver Sun">The Vancouver Sun</TITLE> claimed that the novellas marked her passage from a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">promising</QUOTE> to an <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">established</QUOTE> writer. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mitchell 13" DBREF="64825" QTDIN="QTDINYES">13</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 148" DBREF="64285">148</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Both the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Toronto Star">Toronto Daily Star</TITLE><RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: Should the standard name in the attribute for this be the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Toronto Star</TITLE> ? Apparently the Toronto Star used to be the Toronto Daily Star. img: yes, done.</RESEARCHNOTE> and the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Vancouver Province</TITLE> liked <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Lilly&apos;s Story</TITLE> but had problems with <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Tuesday and Wednesday</TITLE>: the <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> paper called it <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">arty</QUOTE> and the <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> paper described it as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">loose and pointless.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mitchell 13" DBREF="64825" QTDIN="QTDINYES">13</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>In a notice in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Letters in Canada</TITLE> section of the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">University of Toronto Quarterly</TITLE>, <NAME>Claude Bissell</NAME> praised EW&apos;s grace, wit, and fluency in light of her change of subject matter to the lives of the poor, noting that she approached the subject with balanced sympathy and an ironic distance. However, in a concluding appraisal of EW&apos;s work as a whole, while conceding that the novellas were <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">accomplished and delightful</QUOTE> he insisted that they <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">are not major works. She has still to demonstrate her power to sustain a full-length novel (<TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Hetty Dorval</TITLE> was, after all, little more than a novelette, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Innocent Traveller</TITLE> was fragmentary and discursive).</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mitchell 13 and n42" DBREF="64825" QTDIN="QTDINYES">13 and n42</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 149" DBREF="64285">149</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>The poet <NAME>Dorothy Livesay</NAME> (who was a member of a writers&apos; group that met at the Wilsons&apos; apartment, and with whom EW maintained a sometimes tense friendship) wrote of these novellas in <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Ethel Wilson: West Coast Novelist</TITLE>, which appeared in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Saturday Night</TITLE> on <DATE>26 July 1952</DATE>. Though her essay was appreciative, Livesay implied that EW was not fitted to present and judge working-class characters in fiction.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 149" DBREF="64285">149</BIBCIT><RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: this bibcit does not correspond to the information above and I am not sure where this information comes from.</RESEARCHNOTE></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS><NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">John Gray</NAME> attempted to persuade the <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="New York City">New York</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="New York"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG> </PLACE> division of <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Company,, New York">Macmillan</ORGNAME> to publish the two novellas together in an American edition, <TGENREISSUE>but the company thought that two <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVELLA">novellas</TGENRE> had even less of a market than a <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">short-story</TGENRE> collection.</TGENREISSUE> The American division gave the manuscript to <NAME>Ruth May</NAME>, a literary agent who worked to place manuscripts Macmillan could not publish. May was extremely taken by the the stories and earnestly set about finding them a US publisher. After eight months of sending the manuscript to a wide variety of publishing houses and magazines, <ORGNAME STANDARD="HarperCollins Publishing" REG="Harper and Brothers">Harper&apos;s</ORGNAME> eventually decided to publish <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Lilly&apos;s Story</TITLE> by itself in <DATE VALUE="1953-04-">April of 1953</DATE>.</PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS> <PADVERTISING><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Notable American writers including <NAME>Eudora Welty</NAME> and <NAME>Jean Stafford</NAME> praised the book on the dust jacket. <TTONESTYLE>Welty described it as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a moving story, told with wisdom, quietness and power</QUOTE> and Stafford wrote that it was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">made up of so many pleasing and substantial virtues that I hardly know which I savor most, whether the comedy&mdash;sometimes clownish and sometimes sweet&mdash;or Lilly&apos;s winning, bald, unique integrity or the grace and certainty of the writing itself.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 149-150" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">149-150</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TTONESTYLE></RRESPONSES></PADVERTISING></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The <PLACE><GEOG REG="USA">American</GEOG></PLACE> reception was generally positive. <NAME>Stuart Keate</NAME> in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">New York Times Book Review</TITLE> asserted that <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Lilly&apos;s Story</TITLE> established EW as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">one of the most powerful forces to come out of Canada since uranium</QUOTE> and the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">New York Herald Tribune</TITLE> reviewer praised its <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">wise simplicity that makes most other novels seem as if they had been written with battering rams.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mitchell 12" DBREF="64825" QTDIN="QTDINYES">12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">New Yorker</TITLE>, however, dismissed it as an <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">inertly written lesson on how to creep through life.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mitchell 12-13" DBREF="64825" QTDIN="QTDINYES">12-13</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> </RRESPONSES></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The reviews in <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE> were positive. <NAME STANDARD="O&apos;Faolain, Sean">Se&aacute;n O&apos;Faol&aacute;in</NAME><RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: I am not sure how accents are added in Author Editor, but there needs be one above the e in Sean and one above the second a in Faolain. img: our standard form doesn&apos;t use accents, so I added them but standardised. mpo: added accented form as alternative name in authority list</RESEARCHNOTE> wrote in the <ORGNAME>BBC</ORGNAME> journal the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Listener</TITLE> that <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Equations of Love</TITLE> exemplified <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">how English ought to be written,</QUOTE> and called EW <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">one of the most charming and accomplished writers of fiction in English now living. Indeed, this opinion is inadequate to her merits.</QUOTE><RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: this last sentence quoted from the review is not included in the Stouck, so it must have come from another source. </RESEARCHNOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 150" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">150</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> He added that her writing represented an important departure from the majority of writers at the time, who lacked originality. His review was reprinted in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Vancouver News-Herald</TITLE> a few weeks later. <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Equations of Love</TITLE> was also taken up on the radio by a panelist on the <ORGNAME>BBC</ORGNAME> program <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">The Critics</TITLE>. The commentators were divided about EW&apos;s style, which despite her revisions was still characterized by authorial asides and ironic distance. The panelists variously interpreted this as coy, superior, or sympathetic. EW&apos;s half-aunt on the Bryant side, <NAME>Hannah Waller Atkinson</NAME>, wrote to her expressing excitement after hearing the broadcast and also mentioned that EW&apos;s work had been discussed on the program <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Writers on Sunday</TITLE>.</RRESPONSES><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 150-1" DBREF="64285">150-1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><PPERFORMANCE>On <DATE VALUE="1953-01-23">23 January 1953</DATE> a dramatization of <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Lilly&apos;s Story</TITLE> was broadcast on <ORGNAME>CBC</ORGNAME> through <NAME>Robert Weaver</NAME>, the producer of the program <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Canadian Short Stories</TITLE>.</PPERFORMANCE> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The broadcast generated controversy. Newspapers in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Montreal</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Quebec"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> reported that the story featured sexual relations between a Chinese man and a white girl.</RRESPONSES> <RPENALTIES><NAME>David Stouck</NAME> attributes much of the controversy to the tense political climate in Canada at the time, which was influenced by the <NAME STANDARD="McCarthy, Joseph">McCarthy</NAME> investigations in the <PLACE><GEOG REG="USA">US</GEOG></PLACE>. <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Lilly&apos;s Story</TITLE> was cited, Stouck notes, as an example in an inquiry by a special committee of the <ORGNAME>Canadian Senate</ORGNAME> concerning the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">sale and distribution of salacious and indecent literature.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 171-172" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">171-172</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> On <DATE VALUE="1953-02-12">12 February 1953</DATE> one committee member, <NAME>R. W. Keyserlingk</NAME>, described the story as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">sordid . . . told graphically and with extreme poor taste.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 159" DBREF="64885" QTDIN="QTDINYES">159</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Kerserlingk was also unhappy that the broadcast went out between nine and ten in the evening on a Sunday when children were presumed to be still awake. Instead of censuring the story directly for treating an interracial union, he instead suggested that the relationship demeaned both Canadian and Chinese nationality: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Are we not aware that a war in Asia is being fought, not only against communist soldiers, but also for the respect and esteem our world hopes to gain from the peoples of Asia? If so, does the representation of a lecherous Chinese, seducing a pale young slut not imply a false impression of our Chinese friends?</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 159" DBREF="64885" QTDIN="QTDINYES">159</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RPENALTIES> EW did not publicly respond to the debate, which resulted in a great deal of publicity for her writing. <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Canadian novelist <NAME>Morley Callaghan</NAME> responded in her defence when <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Equations of Love</TITLE> was passed over in nominations for a <ORGNAME>Governor General&apos;s Award</ORGNAME>. He remarked on the inferiority of the texts that were nominated and questioned whether the awards committee was truly politically impartial.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 172" DBREF="64285">172</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><PEDITIONS><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Lilly&apos;s Story</TITLE> was translated into German and published in <PLACE><GEOG>Switzerland</GEOG></PLACE> in 1952, entitled simply <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Lilly&apos;s Story">Lilly</TITLE>. This was also the title for the Danish edition which appeared in 1954. Both stories were published in an Italian edition in <DATE VALUE="1958--">1958</DATE>, entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Equations of Love, The">Equazioni d&apos;amore</TITLE>.</PEDITIONS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 159" DBREF="64285">159</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><PSERIALIZATION><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>EW&apos;s American literary agent, <NAME>Ruth May</NAME>, secured a North American newspaper and magazine syndication of <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Lilly&apos;s Story</TITLE></PPERIODICALPUBLICATION> through <ORGNAME>Omnibook</ORGNAME>, which began in the <DATE VALUE="1953-10-" CERTAINTY="C">fall of 1953</DATE>.</PSERIALIZATION> The novella became very well known and <PCIRCULATION>sales were excellent in the <PLACE><GEOG REG="USA">United States</GEOG></PLACE>.</PCIRCULATION> <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL"><ORGNAME STANDARD="HarperCollins Publishing" REG="Harper and Brothers">Harper&apos;s</ORGNAME> reprinted the American edition in 1955. In 1956 <ORGNAME>Avon</ORGNAME> became interested in the story, likely owing to talk of a film version. They bought the rights from <ORGNAME STANDARD="HarperCollins Publishing" REG="Harper and Brothers">Harper&apos;s</ORGNAME> and published a third edition in 1956.</PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER> <PNONBOOKMEDIA><NAME>Ruth May</NAME> had attempted to sell the film rights as early as 1953. <ORGNAME>Twentieth-Century Fox</ORGNAME> made an offer of $5,000, but eventually backed out. <PEARNINGS><NAME>John Patrick</NAME> offered $1,000 for one year&apos;s exclusive option with a further $6,500 if the option was exercised. He did, in fact, exercise the option and paid the additional money in January 1955.</PEARNINGS> <NAME STANDARD="Patrick, John">Patrick</NAME> eventually adapted the story into a screen play entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Equations of Love, The">Feather In Her Hat</TITLE> and in 1963 sold it to <ORGNAME>MGM</ORGNAME>, but a film was never made.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 159-160" DBREF="64285">159-160</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PNONBOOKMEDIA></P><P>In <DATE>April 1954</DATE> the Wilsons were invited to lunch at <PLACE><PLACENAME>Rideau Hall</PLACENAME> in <SETTLEMENT>Ottawa</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> by <NAME>Vincent Massey</NAME>, the Governor General. Massey was a keen patron of the arts and deeply appreciative of EW&apos;s work, particularly <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Equations of Love</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 182" DBREF="64285">182</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>The excitement generated by <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Equations of Love</TITLE> has not carried into current criticism. <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL">However, <NAME>Alice Munro</NAME> has always held EW in extremely high esteem, delighting in her writing style with its <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">hard clear prose, the glaze of perfect sentences.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 160" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">160</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PEDITIONS>Munro wrote an influential afterword for the <DATE VALUE="1990--">1990</DATE> reissue of the full volume,</PEDITIONS> in which she notes that <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Lilly&apos;s Story</TITLE> challenges conventional morality through the heroine&apos;s reliance on lies to achieve her goals. Munro addresses the problem of racism in the depiction of <TCHARACTERNAME>Yow</TCHARACTERNAME>, but notes that every author is to some degree marked by the prejudice of his or her time.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 160" DBREF="64285">160</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Swamp Angel</TITLE></HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="64331" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Swamp Angel, 1954"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="MPO" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1954-08-">August 1954</DATE><CHRONPROSE><RBESTKNOWNWORK><ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Company of Canada Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME> published EW&apos;s <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novel</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Swamp Angel</TITLE>, her best known work.</RBESTKNOWNWORK></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 192" DBREF="64285">192</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>EW first mentioned the story in a letter to <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">John Gray</NAME> in <DATE VALUE="1951-12-">December, 1951</DATE>. At this point she called the story <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Swamp Angel">Country Manners</TITLE>. Another early version entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Swamp Angel">Sweet Influence Doth Impart</TITLE> remained part of the final publication. It depicted the journey of a woman (who would later become <TCHARACTERNAME>Maggie Vardoe</TCHARACTERNAME>) up the <PLACE><REGION>Fraser River</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>. <PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY>In <DATE VALUE="1953-01-">January 1953</DATE> EW wrote to Gray that a manuscript of the larger work was complete and that she was waiting for it to be typed.</PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY> At this point, she called the work <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Swamp Angel">Swamp Angel</TITLE>&mdash;the name of a small, pearl-handled gun that was once in her possession. Like her central character, EW also threw a revolver into the ocean, although in a letter to Gray she did not explain the circumstances of this act, but only said, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I did tell you I threw a revolver into the sea? It is a wonderful experience on a bright day and if done with intention, but it was not our Swamp Angel.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="SEL Stouck 190" DBREF="65165">190</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 184-5" DBREF="64285">184-5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> In a letter to critic <NAME>Desmond Pacey</NAME>, however, EW explained the origins of the pearl-handled revolver: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">My husband&apos;s grandfather (who was old when Wallace knew him) had a little nickel and mother of pearl revolver, very old, and on this little gun were inscribed in a flowing script the words Swamp Angel. He gave it to my husband. I became very much attached to this object&mdash;very very interesting to me because there it lay, inert, incompetent, but with a story (perhaps danger, defense, death) implicit. We knew nothing of its origins. I had it always in sight.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 191" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">191</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></QUOTE> In the novel&apos;s epigraph, she added that historically the original <SOCALLED>Swamp Angel</SOCALLED> was the name of a massive gun mounted in a swamp during the 1863 siege of <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Charleston</SETTLEMENT>, <REGION>South Carolina</REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE>, and that subsequently revolvers were issued with the same name. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 191-2" DBREF="64285">191-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>In a letter of <DATE>25 July 1953</DATE> to editor <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">John Gray</NAME>, EW sounded characteristically uneasy about the worth of the new manuscript. First, she expressed some anxiety about the scope of her themes, reflecting on her works as a whole. She wrote: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">My genre is very limited. . . . As for the writing &mdash;that is the only way I can write&mdash;of beauty and emotion, and then with a horrid fear of sentimentality, tipping it back on the other side with a flat statement. The thing is to get the balance.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="SEL Stouck 186" DBREF="65165">186</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She also described some of her anxiety as the result of the excitement surrounding <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Equations of Love</TITLE>. In her words: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">A slight hazard occurs in the writer&apos;s mind when the last book has been extravagently praised by some critics. One would rather not publish than publish something with little merit.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="SEL Stouck 186" DBREF="65165">186</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL"><NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">Gray</NAME>&apos;s first response expressed some reservations: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">we believe this is in the way of being the best book you have done, but none of us has the feeling of it being satisfactory yet.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 186" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">186</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> Once again, the piece seemed to force two stories together, lacking structural coherence. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 187" DBREF="64285">187</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PATTITUDES>Despite these reservations, <NAME>David Stouck</NAME> notes that Gray and EW had an extraordinarily fruitful relationship. Wilson took Gray&apos;s criticism very well. After hoping for his sake that he <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">didn&apos;t feel the least twinge in writing,</QUOTE> she went on to say: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Of course you didn&apos;t, the way is always open between us.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 187" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">187</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Swamp Angel</TITLE> concerns a <TTHEMETOPIC>woman&apos;s struggle for emancipation</TTHEMETOPIC>. It also emphasizes the importance of landscape and place in the search for and creation of meaning. <TPLOT><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL"><TCHARACTERNAME>Maggie Lloyd Vardoe</TCHARACTERNAME> escapes a <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="unhappy marriage">stifling marriage</TMOTIF> in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT REG="Vancouver">Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE></TSETTINGPLACE> <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="IDENTIFIABLE">and realizes her true worth by helping to manage and restore a run-down resort at <SOCALLED>Three Loon Lake</SOCALLED>, which is based on EW&apos;s beloved <PLACE><PLACENAME>Lac Le Jeune</PLACENAME><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>.</TSETTINGPLACE> The main plot line concerns Maggie. Her success is compromised by one of her employers, <TCHARACTERNAME>Vera Gunnarsen</TCHARACTERNAME>, who is jealous of Maggie and makes life difficult for her. The two women come together when Vera attempts <TMOTIF>suicide</TMOTIF> and Maggie tries to nurse her back into physical and spiritual health. Whether or not she succeeds is uncertain. A secondary plot line concerns <TCHARACTERNAME>Nell Severance</TCHARACTERNAME>, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>retired circus performer</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, and her daughter <TCHARACTERNAME>Hilda Severance</TCHARACTERNAME>: a middle-aged woman who marries and has a child. <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Severance, Nell">Mrs Severance</TCHARACTERNAME>&apos;s circus act centred on her ability to <TTHEMETOPIC>juggle fire</TTHEMETOPIC> and on a type of revolver known as a <SOCALLED>swamp angel</SOCALLED>. Decisions made about the revolver, or inspired by the revolver, tie together otherwise disjointed subplots. Mrs Severance decides to move on with her life by parting with the revolver. She sends it to Maggie with instructions to throw it into the lake upon her death; this rite takes place in the final scenes of the novel.</TPLOT> Compassionate characterizations and acutely detailed descriptions account for the power of this narrative of <TTHEMETOPIC>liberation</TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Pacey 137-8" DBREF="65266">137-8</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 188" DBREF="64285">188</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><TCHARACTERIZATION><TCHARACTERNAME REG="Vardoe, Maggie Lloyd">Maggie</TCHARACTERNAME> can be seen as another manifestation of <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Waller, Lilly">Lilly</TCHARACTERNAME> from <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Lilly&apos;s Story</TITLE> in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Equations of Love</TITLE>. Both are <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">independent women</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who attempt to create a new lives and manage to do so through sheer determination. Mrs Severance can also be thought of as a parallel to <TCHARACTERNAME>Mrs Emblem</TCHARACTERNAME> from <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Lilly&apos;s Story</TITLE>. Both are <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>sensuous, good-natured and wise</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, but Mrs Severance can at times be scathingly harsh. To other characters, she is a source of both guidance and <TMOTIF>violence</TMOTIF>. Maggie and Mrs Severance are each seen in various lights which depend on the point of view of the character observing them.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Pacey 138, 140-1" DBREF="65266">138, 140-1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TCHARACTERIZATION></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PEDITIONS>The <PLACE><GEOG REG="USA">US</GEOG></PLACE> edition of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Swamp Angel</TITLE> was published by <ORGNAME STANDARD="HarperCollins Publishing" REG="Harper and Brothers">Harper&apos;s</ORGNAME> at the same time as the Canadian edition. During negotiations over it, Harper&apos;s readers felt that the story was too slight and that too many characters were simply sketches. In response EW wrote two more chapters relating <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Gunnarsen, Vera">Vera</TCHARACTERNAME>&apos;s background and unhappy childhood, and added a paragraph describing Maggie rowing. She thought the additions improved the story, as she further indicated by sending <NAME>Audrey Butler</NAME> a copy of the <ORGNAME STANDARD="HarperCollins Publishing" REG="Harper and Brothers">Harper&apos;s</ORGNAME> edition instead of the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishing Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME>.</PEDITIONS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 192-3" DBREF="64285">192-3</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P>The reviews appeared in the month of publication. <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">On 21 August <NAME>William Arthur Deacon</NAME> at the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Globe and Mail</TITLE>, finally won over, wrote that in contrast to EW&apos;s other work, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Swamp Angel</TITLE> was unified and <TCHARACTERNAME>Maggie Lloyd Vardoe</TCHARACTERNAME> was a terrific character. He praised EW for her ability to communicate a depth of meaning with great economy, remarking upon her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">sure selection of incidents and dialogues. . . . Would that more novelists could convey so much so briefly.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 193" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">193</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> In <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Canadian Forum</TITLE>, <NAME>Hilda Kirkwood</NAME> further praised EW&apos;s distinct style, as well as her attention to place. Positive reviews also appeared in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Vancouver Province</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Toronto Star">Toronto Daily Star</TITLE> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Winnipeg Tribune</TITLE>. <PLACE><GEOG REG="USA">American</GEOG></PLACE> critics qualified their praise. The the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">New York Herald Tribune</TITLE> praised EW&apos;s style and descriptive skill, but found the plot ultimately inconclusive (echoing <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">John Gray</NAME>&apos;s original worry). The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">New York Times</TITLE> found Maggie&apos;s plot and that of the Severances to be disjointed. In <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE> the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Times Literary Supplement</TITLE> echoed the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">New York Herald Tribune</TITLE>, praising the description of <PLACE><REGION>British Columbia</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> but finding the descriptive strength insufficient compensation for narrative weakness.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 193-4" DBREF="64285">193-4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="IMAGERY"><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Swamp Angel</TITLE> has enjoyed critical attention in academia as a result of its rich symbolism. <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RE-EVALUATION" FORMALITY="FORMAL">In his introduction to the <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">New Canadian Library</TITLE> edition, <NAME>Desmond Pacey</NAME> examines various animals in the story for their complex symbolism, but focuses in particular on the gun.<RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: this information about Pacey&apos;s examination of the animals and the gun is not explicitly mentioned in the source. Is this okay?</RESEARCHNOTE></RRESPONSES></TTECHNIQUES> <PATTITUDES>EW had mixed feelings about the <PLITERARYSCHOOLS INVOLVEMENT="INVOLVEMENTNO" REG="New Criticism">New Critics&apos;</PLITERARYSCHOOLS> emphasis on symbols, which she expressed in a letter to Pacey on <DATE VALUE="1964-04-16">16 April 1964</DATE>. She thought that writers might self-consciously cultivate symbols in order to conform to reviewers&apos; expectations and thus lose their own natural or <SOCALLED>intrinsic</SOCALLED> qualities. In light of this possibility, EW described herself as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">positively anti-symbol.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="SEL Stouck 234" DBREF="65165" QTDIN="QTDINYES">234</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> However, with time she came to realize that perhaps symbolism is beyond a writer&apos;s personal control, and depends on the reader&apos;s interpretation.</PATTITUDES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RE-EVALUATION" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME STANDARD="Pacey, Desmond">Pacey</NAME> further described EW as a Christian humanist, remarking that lonely and downtrodden characters are redeemed in her works only through Christ-like compassion.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="SEL Stouck 234" DBREF="65165">234</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 196-7" DBREF="64285">196-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RE-EVALUATION" FORMALITY="FORMAL" GENDEREDRESPONSE="GENDEREDYES">Feminist responses to EW&apos;s work emerged in the 1970s. <TCHARACTERNAME>Maggie Lloyd Vardoe</TCHARACTERNAME>&apos;s decision to leave a <TMOTIF>loveless marriage</TMOTIF> and independently pursue a more fulfilling one was lauded as radical for its time. In the 1980s, critics focussed on more complex and subtle elements of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Swamp Angel</TITLE>. <NAME>Heather Murray</NAME> argued that the novel is not realistic in a conventional sense, that it contains metafictional elements such as multiple voices, and that it is often difficult to distinguish between the narrative itself and the narration. <TVOICENARRATION>Noting Murray&apos;s contribution, <NAME>David Stouck</NAME> quotes a passage from the novel where at least four possible voices can be identified:<QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><QUOTE DIRECT="N">[D]on&apos;t forget the chops darling.</QUOTE> At the word chops she lay down again. She would feel better later in the day. People said Really Hilda you look lovely. How enchanting, how devastating the future of humanity. She felt she had always known this, which was not the case.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 201" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">201</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The passage dispenses with standard grammar and punctuation. It resembles <NAME>Virginia Woolf</NAME>&apos;s or <NAME>William Faulkner</NAME>&apos;s stream-of-consciousness style by incorporating multiple, sometimes unidentifiable voices in order to express a character&apos;s psychological experience. These multiple voices have been praised by later critics, but in EW&apos;s time they were often interpreted by readers and editors as distracting authorial intrusions.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 197, 201-2" DBREF="64285">197, 201-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TVOICENARRATION></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PEDITIONS><RESEARCHNOTE>img: deleted repetitious statement here.</RESEARCHNOTE>In <DATE>1962</DATE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Swamp Angel</TITLE> became the first of EW&apos;s works to be reprinted in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">New Canadian Library</TITLE> series. <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>The cover features a not particularly appealing drawing of EW.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS> The book was reissued by <ORGNAME>McClelland and Stewart</ORGNAME> in 1982 as one of the <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES" REG="New Canadian Library">New Canadian Library Classics</TITLE> and again in 1990 along with EW&apos;s complete works. The 1990 reprinting followed the American edition. It included an afterword by <NAME>George Bowering</NAME>, who noted EW&apos;s extraordinary contribution to Canadian literature and in particular praised her achievements as a stylist. A <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Canadian Critical Edition</TITLE> published by <ORGNAME>Tecumseh Press</ORGNAME> in 2005 does not reprint either the Canadian or the American edition, but is based on the surviving manuscript and collated with the early editions. It includes essays by <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">John Gray</NAME>, <NAME>Anjali Bhelande</NAME>, <NAME>David Stouck</NAME>, and <NAME>W. J. Keith</NAME> among others, and is edited by <NAME>Li-Ping Geng</NAME>.</PEDITIONS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 192-3, 205" DBREF="64285">192-3, 205</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Love and Salt Water</TITLE></HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="64332" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Love and Salt Water, 1956"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="MPO" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>September 1956</DATE><CHRONPROSE><ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishing Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME> issued EW&apos;s final full-length fiction, the <TGENRE GENRENAME="ROMANCE">romance</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Love and Salt Water</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 224" DBREF="64285">224</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>In addition to matters of love and relationships, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Love and Salt Water</TITLE> explicitly engages with <TTHEMETOPIC>ethical and philosophical issues</TTHEMETOPIC>. EW downplayed its depth, calling it a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">temperate affair like the water and climate of our shores.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mitchell 44" DBREF="64825" QTDIN="QTDINYES">44</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Like most of her other works, it left early traces in her correspondence with editor <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">John Gray</NAME>. On <DATE VALUE="1953-08-22">22 August 1953</DATE>, while working on <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Swamp Angel</TITLE>, she wrote, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I have, hang it all, unintentionally started another [story] that flows like cream of some kind, with almost too much facility.</QUOTE> She continued, however: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Don&apos;t think I&apos;m abandoning <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Swamp Angel">S. A.</TITLE> in favour of something else.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="SEL Stouck 190" DBREF="65165">190</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PARCHIVALLOCATION>The <SOCALLED>something else</SOCALLED> was in fact an early draft of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Love and Salt Water</TITLE>, originally titled <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Love and Salt Water">Miss Cuppy</TITLE>. In EW&apos;s papers at the <ORGNAME>University of British Columbia</ORGNAME>, the early draft has the alternative title <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Love and Salt Water">Herself While Young</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 218" DBREF="64285">218</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PARCHIVALLOCATION></P><P><TVOICENARRATION>The early manuscript of <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Love and Salt Water">Miss Cuppy</TITLE> departs from EW&apos;s work significantly, as it is written in the first person. <TCHARACTERNAME>Ellen Cuppy</TCHARACTERNAME> explicitly announces her intention to write a book. After considering the problem of <TTHEMETOPIC>memory</TTHEMETOPIC> in relating history (<QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Then as years pass, memory becomes full of holes, and events (but not persons) fall through</QUOTE>), she struggles with her narrative voice. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I am sorry to speak in this stilted way</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 219" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">219</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Ellen&apos;s reflections grow increasingly self-conscious and blur the lines between narrator and author. The style is particularly unusual given that EW abhorred self-consciousness in style&mdash;which she considered pretentious and unnatural&mdash;in other writers.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 166-7, 219" DBREF="64285">166-7, 219</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TVOICENARRATION>= <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL"><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">Upon reading the completed manuscript, <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">Gray</NAME> wrote in July 1954: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I was completely captivated by the story of Miss Cuppy, and by the intricate art of this little symphony.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 220" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">220</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Six weeks later, his response changed dramatically as a result of the readers&apos; reports at <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishing Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME>. Conscious of this shift, he prefaced his summary of the reports by saying: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">In spite of the memory of many beautiful and stimulating parts of the book, I think I must agree substantially with this comment.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 221" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">221</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The reports were harsh. One reader thought the draft contained no evidence of a story and appeared to be more of a notebook. The second reader commented on the prevalence of digressive elements, including remarks on <TTHEMETOPIC>writers</TTHEMETOPIC> and observations about <TTHEMETOPIC>flora and fauna</TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 221" DBREF="64285">221</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES><PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS>Unusually, Gray did not screen the severity of this criticism from EW. Instead he pointed out that the readers&apos; charge of a lack of focus reminded him of negative criticisms of her previous books. There is no record of EW&apos;s reply, but it is clear she put the project on hold for some time.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 221" DBREF="64285">221</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER></P><P>She rewrote the novel in some downtime after Wallace&apos;s heart attack in 1954. The revised version was chronologically straightforward and Ellen was no longer a writer. Another change in plot concerned Ellen&apos;s <TTHEMETOPIC>broken engagement</TTHEMETOPIC>. Instead of being romantically deceived, Ellen now finds that her feelings change toward the man she is supposed to marry. <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">EW eliminated many digressions, as well as the epigraph from <NAME>Thomas Browne</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Religio Medici</TITLE> which read <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">we carry with us the wonders we seek without us; There is all <EMPH>Africa</EMPH> and her prodigies in us.</QUOTE></TINTERTEXTUALITY><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 221, 222" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">221, 222</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER RELATIONSHIPTYPE="PROFESSIONAL">Gray received the revised manuscript on <DATE>15 February 1955</DATE> and responded with high praise. However, he also maintained that the overall story was still disjointed, the authorial intrusions were too frequent, and the characters still seemed underdeveloped. EW submitted a third draft (by <DATE VALUE="1955-10-03" CERTAINTY="BY">3 October 1955</DATE>) with an alternative tragic ending in which <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="death of heroine">Ellen drowns at sea</TMOTIF> and her body is never found. Suggested new titles included <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Love and Salt Water">Nothing is Safe</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="Love and Salt Water">Unimportant People</TITLE>, and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Love and Salt Water</TITLE>. In letters about this latest revision, EW noted that many of her works depict drowning: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I don&apos;t quite understand how the feeling of the sea is so dominant. I have never known anyone who was drowned. </QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 223" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">223</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She also remarked on a second pattern she called <SOCALLED>obsessive</SOCALLED>: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Although I never knew my mother . . . the <TTHEMETOPIC>mother-child relationship</TTHEMETOPIC> occurs in nearly every story.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 223" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">223</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Stouck observes that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the absence of a mother as a firm anchor in life seems all too easily connected to the sea and drowning and a world where <QUOTE DIRECT="N">Nothing is Safe</QUOTE>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 223" DBREF="64285">223</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS>Gray ultimately suggested he would let the <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> division of <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Publishers Limited">Macmillan</ORGNAME> decide if the manuscript was ready for publication. Characteristically, EW lost confidence in her work and wrote to ask for its withdrawal. <PCONTRACT>However, the English division was extremely receptive and wished to proceed to a contract.</PCONTRACT></PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS> It was decided that the <TMOTIF>happy ending</TMOTIF> was preferable. The book was published in September 1956.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 222-24" DBREF="64285">222-24</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER> </P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TPLOT><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Love and Salt Water</TITLE>, using the romance formula of a <TTHEMETOPIC>journey through misfortune and misunderstanding to re-integration within a family and community</TTHEMETOPIC>, recounts <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL"><TCHARACTERNAME>Ellen Cuppy</TCHARACTERNAME>&apos;s experiences travelling to <PLACE><AREA>Europe</AREA></PLACE>, serving as a <ORGNAME STANDARD="Women&apos;s Royal Navy Service"><TCHARACTERTYPEROLE PROTAGONIST="FEMALE">WREN</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE></ORGNAME>, working in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Saskatoon</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Saskatchewan"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>, surviving a <TTHEMETOPIC>boating accident</TTHEMETOPIC> which leaves a <TTHEMETOPIC>disfiguring scar</TTHEMETOPIC> on her face, and realizing that her fianc&eacute; loves her as she is.</TSETTINGPLACE></TPLOT> Like <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Innocent Traveller</TITLE>, the novel contains autobiographical elements, such as a <TTHEMETOPIC>mother&apos;s sudden death</TTHEMETOPIC> and a <TTHEMETOPIC>broken engagement</TTHEMETOPIC>, <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL">and again it depicts the <PLACE>coast of <REGION REG="British Columbia">B. C.</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE> personally and lovingly.</TSETTINGPLACE> Although the plot is conventional, overall the work contains many unconventional elements, including numerous <TTHEMETOPIC>sudden deaths</TTHEMETOPIC> and disfigurement. Nothing is safe here on psychological, emotional, and physical levels.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 224" DBREF="64285">224</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>EW related a personal experience that prompted her to write this story: an image of a mother, father, and small daughter in <PLACE><PLACENAME>Stanley Park</PLACENAME>, <SETTLEMENT>Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE>. She said the family presented an image of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">health, companionship, and unusual physical beauty. . . . They were of a more privileged order than of Lilly, or Mort, or Myrtle, or Miss Tritt . . . but I decided to make them my story, by the sea, whatever might happen to them. Nothing much, I thought, might happen to them, any more than happens to most such pleasant people whom we meet daily in our lives.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Mitchell 44" DBREF="64825" QTDIN="QTDINYES">44</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></QUOTE> <TCHARACTERIZATION>In her memoir <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Life of Ethel Wilson</TITLE>, <NAME>Mary McAlpine</NAME>, who was a friend of the author, claimed that <TCHARACTERNAME>Ellen Cuppy</TCHARACTERNAME> was based on her and that EW had told this to John Gray and two other mutual friends. Wilson had also, however, surprised McAlpine by writing in a letter that Ellen Cuppy was based on <NAME>Sylvia Farrow</NAME> (editor at <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Publishers Limited">Macmillan</ORGNAME>).  McAlpine said Wilson often led friends and publishing acquaintances down false tracks.</TCHARACTERIZATION> She also wrote that EW had once brought up the subject of the manuscript of <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Love and Salt Water</TITLE> (something she had not done before) and consulted McAlpine on the two possible endings.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="McAlpine 171-2" DBREF="64885">171-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Regardless of actual character models, the work returns to familiar types. The self-reliant central character, <TCHARACTERNAME>Ellen Cuppy</TCHARACTERNAME>, resembles <TCHARACTERNAME>Lilly Waller</TCHARACTERNAME> and <TCHARACTERNAME>Maggie Lloyd Vardoe</TCHARACTERNAME>. The <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>controlling, jealous and neurotic</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> <TCHARACTERNAME>Vera Gunnerson</TCHARACTERNAME> from <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Swamp Angel</TITLE> reappears as <TCHARACTERNAME>Nora Cuppy</TCHARACTERNAME>, Ellen&apos;s sister. The wise elderly woman (<TCHARACTERNAME>Mrs Emblem</TCHARACTERNAME> in <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Tuesday and Wednesday</TITLE>, <TCHARACTERNAME>Mrs Severance</TCHARACTERNAME> in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Swamp Angel</TITLE>) here returns as <TCHARACTERNAME REG="Peake, Mary">Aunt Mary Peake</TCHARACTERNAME>. <TCHARACTERNAME>Maud Sneddon</TCHARACTERNAME>, a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>lonely single woman</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, resembles <TCHARACTERNAME>Victoria May Tritt</TCHARACTERNAME> of <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Tuesday and Wednesday</TITLE>.</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><NAME>Desmond Pacey</NAME> argues, however, that in each case the characterization is weaker than before: Aunt Mary Peake <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">never utters any speeches as memorable as those of Mrs. Emblem and Mrs. Severance, and is altogether less subtly and complexly portrayed,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Pacey 159" DBREF="65266" QTDIN="QTDINYES">159</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> while <TCHARACTERNAME>Ellen Cuppy</TCHARACTERNAME> is less sympathetic, because of her privileged life, than Lilly or Maggie.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Pacey 160" DBREF="65266">160</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Reviews for <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Love and Salt Water</TITLE> revealed that EW was increasingly respected primarily as a distinguished stylist. An exceptionally negative review appeared in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Edmonton Journal</TITLE>, which described the novel as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a ridiculous book</QUOTE> and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a waste of time.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 225" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">225</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>Other Canadian reviews were much more positive. <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Vancouver Province">The Vancouver Province</TITLE> called EW the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">First Lady of Letters in Canada</QUOTE> and lauded her for capturing the West Coast&apos;s <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">special tang</QUOTE> and for her <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">telegraphic</QUOTE> prose style.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 226" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">226</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Montreal Gazette</TITLE>, too, praised the style as simple but effective. <NAME>William Arthur Deacon</NAME> of the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Globe and Mail</TITLE> called the novel <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a muted drama of repressed emotions</QUOTE> rendered in the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">chaste, restrained style</QUOTE> that was typical of EW.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 226" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">226</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Although Deacon&apos;s nationalist sensibility had often clashed with EW&apos;s public dismissal of the idea of a national literature, he found consolation in her descriptive language of distinctly Canadian places which demonstrated how <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the formidable power of geography determines the character and performance of a people.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 226" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">226</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Despite the fact that Deacon still considered the characters to be weak and the plot to be thin at best, he nonetheless called EW one of Canada&apos;s most distinguished writers.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 226-7" DBREF="64285">226-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Other reviewers could not get over the lack of a substantial plot, or find sufficient compensation in EW&apos;s style. In <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Queen&apos;s Quarterly</TITLE>, Canadian poet <NAME>Miriam Waddington</NAME> connected the perceived lack of substance in the novel with the affluence of its characters. The fact that they <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">travel in airplanes, have no money problems, play badminton, and don&apos;t read much,</QUOTE> would, she believed, alienate readers.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 227" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">227</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL">In her <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Cross-Cultural Reckonings</TITLE>, 1995, <NAME>Blanche H. Gelfant</NAME> focuses specifically on the function of <TTHEMETOPIC>class</TTHEMETOPIC> in the text. She notes that <TCHARACTERNAME>Frank Cuppy</TCHARACTERNAME> is a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>quintessential capitalist</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> who unceasingly pursues profit and seeks to compensate by lavish gifts for his detachment from family life. According to Gelfant, the plot is driven by <TTHEMETOPIC>profit and greed</TTHEMETOPIC>, but this fact is carefully obscured. The working class is effaced: on the freighter crewmen are hidden from passengers, and in hotels the cooks are hidden from guests to create the illusion that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">nobody works</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 227" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">227</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <NAME>David Stouck</NAME> argues many passages in the book link EW&apos;s literary preoccupation to her personal history as a displaced orphan. He writes: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">When one of the characters says to herself, <QUOTE DIRECT="N">Do we always live on a brink, then?</QUOTE> (161), Wilson takes us, I believe, to the very heart of her imaginative world.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 224" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">224</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>He goes on to point out many parallels between EW&apos;s life and Ellen Cuppy&apos;s experiences.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 224-5" DBREF="64285">224-5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PEDITIONS><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Love and Salt Water</TITLE> was reprinted by the <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">New Canadian Library</TITLE> in 1990 along with the rest of Wilson&apos;s work, with an afterword written by Canadian poet <NAME>Anne Marriott</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 231" DBREF="64285">231</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Mrs. Golightly and other stories</TITLE></HEADING><DIV2><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="64334" PLACEHOLDER="EW, Mrs Golightly and Other Stories, 1961"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1961-10-">October 1961</DATE><CHRONPROSE>EW&apos;s final volume, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Mrs. Golightly and other <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">stories</TGENRE></TITLE>, appeared from <ORGNAME STANDARD="Macmillan Canada" REG="Macmillan Publishers Ltd">Macmillan</ORGNAME>. Its critical success, and the way that later Canadian anthologies drew on it, established Wilson as a master of short fiction.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 251-2" DBREF="64285">251-2</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>In January 1956, EW began work on a new manuscript. At the end of a talk given on 24 January 1957 at the <ORGNAME STANDARD="University of British Columbia">UBC</ORGNAME> Library, she told her audience she was working on <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a book with a real origin, a real anger, a real purpose.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 234-5" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">234-5</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She sent the work entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">The Vat and the Brew</TITLE> to <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">John Gray</NAME> on <DATE>27 March 1957</DATE>. It was less a work of fiction than a moral tract concerning <TTHEMETOPIC>youth crime and delinquency in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="British Columbia"></REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC>. At this time EW had developed a deep interest in this topic and kept a file of newspaper clippings about it. On one of her trips to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>London</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE> with her husband, she visited a courtroom and observed the sentencing of prostitutes and drug dealers.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 235-6" DBREF="64285">235-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Her manuscript condemns lower-class parents who disrupt family life and put their children at risk, particularly mothers who work in order to achieve petty material gains beyond the necessities of life. The <SOCALLED>vat</SOCALLED> of her title is thus the dysfunctional family home, while the <SOCALLED>brew</SOCALLED> is the crime and delinquency produced among youth by irresponsible parents. In the story <TPLOT><TCHARACTERNAME>Dorothy</TCHARACTERNAME> gets lofty ideas from <TTHEMETOPIC>magazines</TTHEMETOPIC> in the absence of adequate <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">mental and spiritual food.</QUOTE> <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 235" DBREF="64285">235</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She abandons her family, including her young son <TCHARACTERNAME>Lennie</TCHARACTERNAME>, and moves to <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Hollywood</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="California"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE> to become a famous actress. Her son is eventually<TTHEMETOPIC> imprisoned for <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="murder">killing</TMOTIF> a police officer</TTHEMETOPIC>.</TPLOT></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER><PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS>Despite her evident passion regarding the material, <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">John Gray</NAME> wrote to EW on <DATE>30 April 1957</DATE> to say that <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">The Vat and the Brew</TITLE> was not publishable.</PSUBMISSIONSREJECTIONS> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL">He noted that the characters were impossible to sympathize with and that the narrator&apos;s superior attitude was suffocating for the reader. Furthermore, EW&apos;s depiction of the language and slang of Vancouver&apos;s seedy underside seemed forced and unnatural. Gray asked Professor <NAME>D. J. Conacher</NAME> to read reworked versions of the draft in the collection that would become <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Mrs. Golightly and other stories</TITLE>. While Conacher appreciated most of EW&apos;s work, he judged these specific stories to be inferior. Other opinions found them <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">as full of stale cliches as church social work</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 249" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">249</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and, perhaps unfairly, that EW seemed too much preoccupied with condemning other people&apos;s children.</RRESPONSES><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 235-6, 249" DBREF="64285">235-6, 249</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PRELATIONSWITHPUBLISHER></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>After rejecting <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">The Vat and the Brew</TITLE>, <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">John Gray</NAME> nonetheless encouraged EW to continue writing stories and indicated that publishing a collection might be possible. In a letter dated <DATE>20 November 1958</DATE>, EW sketched out a series of potential titles for a volume in which she hoped to reprint several stories, particularly <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Tuesday and Wednesday</TITLE>, which was, she said, her favourite work. <PATTITUDES>By the next fall, however, she was once again plagued with doubt about the project. After sending the collection for a reading in September 1959, she wrote to Gray to stop the project, because of her husband&apos;s illness and her own exhaustion.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="SEL Stouck 211-12" DBREF="65165">211-12</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 159, 246" DBREF="64285">159, 246</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES> Her interest revived in the spring of 1960, <PEARNINGS>when her confidence may have been boosted by a series of external requests for short stories, which led to the sale of <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">From Flores</TITLE> for $1,000.</PEARNINGS> The proposal was now for a volume whose contents would include two works of non-fiction about London written a few years earlier. These were <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Corner of X and Y Streets</TITLE>, about <TTHEMETOPIC>post-war <PLACE><SETTLEMENT CURRENT="London" REG="Soho">Soho</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Middlesex"></REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE><RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: for Soho, the current is filled in as London, but the Reg is filled in as Soho. Should the Reg be filled in with London? img: correct as is.</RESEARCHNOTE></TTHEMETOPIC> and <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">To Keep the Memory of So Worthy a Friend</TITLE>, a tribute to <TTHEMETOPIC>actors <NAME>Henry Condell</NAME> and <NAME>John Heminges</NAME> who collected <NAME STANDARD="Shakespeare, William">Shakespeare</NAME>&apos;s plays in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Comedies, Histories, and Tragedies">First Folio</TITLE></TTHEMETOPIC> after the playwright&apos;s death, registering their collection on <DATE>8 November 1623</DATE>. A third piece of non-fiction, concerning the <RS REG="ship">St Roch</RS>, an <TTHEMETOPIC>ice-breaking ship</TTHEMETOPIC> that first explored the Canadian arctic, did not in the end not make it into the final collection. Gray again consulted Professor <NAME STANDARD="Conacher, D. J.">Conacher</NAME> at the <ORGNAME>University of Toronto</ORGNAME> in the assessment of the new manuscript. <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">Overall, Conacher deemed the collection strong and pleasingly varied in form, including social comedies, scenery sketches, and EW&apos;s more traditional didactic narratives.</RRESPONSES> This second proposal was quite close to the eventual collection.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 248-9" DBREF="64285">248-249</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Mrs. Golightly and other stories</TITLE>, as published in October of 1961, comprised eighteen stories. These are a blend of republished work (<TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">Hurry, Hurry</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">I Just Love Dogs</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">We Have to Sit Opposite</TITLE>) with earlier unpublished work (<TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Corner of X and Y Streets</TITLE>) and new stories (<TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Truth and Mrs Forrester</TITLE>, <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">The Window</TITLE>).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 245, 248, 251, 254" DBREF="64285">245, 248, 251, 254</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="SEL Stouck 212" DBREF="65165">212</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="FORMAL">The book&apos;s reception was very positive. Without a single main plot to analyze, reviewers once again primarily discussed EW&apos;s distinctive style, and her precision with language was often noted. In the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Vancouver Sun</TITLE>, the reviewer observed that EW&apos;s status as a <TGENRE GENRENAME="REGIONAL">regional</TGENRE> writer should be celebrated instead of considered a limitation. In the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL" REG="Toronto Star">Toronto Daily Star</TITLE>, <NAME>Robert Weaver</NAME> commented that the work demonstrated a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">quiet intellectual toughness.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 251" DBREF="64285">251</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Three reviewers noted that the stories had a <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">New Yorker</TITLE> quality. One criticism came from <NAME>Hilda Kirkwood</NAME> in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Saturday Night</TITLE> concerning the story <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">We Have to Sit Opposite</TITLE>. Kirkwood found <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">anti-German sentiment</QUOTE> in the story, which, she wrote, was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">not worthy of so large-hearted a writer.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 251" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">251</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <TSETTINGDATE SETTINGDATETYPE="PAST">(This story was actually based on EW&apos;s experiences travelling in the late 1920s, although many reviewers read it as an allegory of the Second World War.)</TSETTINGDATE> <PCIRCULATION>Although the collection was EW&apos;s most critically successful work, it did not sell well.</PCIRCULATION> <PANTHOLOGIZATION>However, many of the stories have become favourites in anthologies of Canadian short fiction.</PANTHOLOGIZATION> <TGENREISSUE>Their wide circulation has contributed to the common conception that EW was primarily a <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">short story</TGENRE> writer as opposed to a <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOVEL">novelist</TGENRE>.</TGENREISSUE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 251-2" DBREF="64285">251-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PEDITIONS><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Mrs. Golightly and other stories</TITLE> was reprinted in the <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">New Canadian Library</TITLE> series in 1990 with an afterword by <NAME>David Stouck</NAME>. Stouck notes that EW herself was aware that her work was best suited to shorter forms. In his critical biography of her, he further notes that the collection is filled with questions concerning the <TTHEMETOPIC>relationship between identity, place and truth</TTHEMETOPIC>.</PEDITIONS> <PNONBOOKMEDIA>An animated short film of the story <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">From Flores</TITLE> was funded by the <ORGNAME>National Film Board</ORGNAME> in 1990 and featured the voice of <NAME STANDARD="MacKay, Don,, actor">Don MacKay</NAME>.</PNONBOOKMEDIA><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="OCLC" DBREF="1709"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 255-6" DBREF="64285">255-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Expressing her Literary Opinions</HEADING><DIV2><HEADING>Public Speaking</HEADING><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>While working on the collection that became <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Mrs. Golightly and other stories</TITLE>, EW began a series of <TGENRE GENRENAME="SPEECH">public speaking engagements</TGENRE>. She gave a talk at the <ORGNAME>University of British Columbia</ORGNAME> on <DATE VALUE="1956-01-28">January 28, 1956</DATE>, entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">How Does a Writer Reach His Audience?</TITLE> in which she specifically addressed <TTHEMETOPIC>writing in <PLACE><REGION>British Columbia</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"></GEOG></PLACE></TTHEMETOPIC>. She expressed here her well-known opinion against <TTHEMETOPIC>national literature</TTHEMETOPIC>: <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE"><QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I was much pleased by the words of a novelist from (I think) Montreal, by the name of <NAME>Mordecai Richler</NAME>. He was asked, <QUOTE DIRECT="N">Do you call yourself a Canadian writer or a Jewish writer?</QUOTE> He said, <QUOTE DIRECT="N">Neither. I call myself a writer.</QUOTE></QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 215" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">215</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY> EW also spoke with <NAME>Joyce Cary</NAME> for <ORGNAME>CBC</ORGNAME> radio&apos;s program <TITLE TITLETYPE="SERIES">Anthology</TITLE> which aired on <DATE VALUE="1957-01-22">January 22, 1957</DATE>. <DATE VALUE="1967-01-24">Two days later</DATE> she spoke again at the <ORGNAME STANDARD="University of British Columbia">UBC</ORGNAME> library. The talk was titled <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">Somewhere Near the Truth</TITLE>. In it, EW expressed her scepticism concerning the idea that <TTHEMETOPIC>art is a psychological expression of inner conflict</TTHEMETOPIC>. She was also dismissive of the attention paid to <TTHEMETOPIC>symbols in literary criticism</TTHEMETOPIC>. She argued instead that writing is born out of the desire to understand those around us and that it is often motivated by the <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">sheer <TTHEMETOPIC>delight in writing</TTHEMETOPIC>.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 233, 234" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">233, 234</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P><PATTITUDES>EW expressed to <NAME STANDARD="Gray, John,, editor">John Gray</NAME> some self-doubt as to whether she was truly qualified to speak to a university audience: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">How pretentious of me [to speak], who <SIC>have</SIC> nothing but a very treasured <EMPH>conferred</EMPH> degree, &amp; <EMPH>know</EMPH> nothing.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 234" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">234</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PATTITUDES> Nevertheless she spoke again at <ORGNAME>West Vancouver Highschool</ORGNAME> and again in <DATE VALUE="1958-03-">March of 1958</DATE> at <ORGNAME STANDARD="University of British Columbia">UBC</ORGNAME>&apos;s School of Architecture. At UBC she once again repeated her sceptical view regarding the value of <TTHEMETOPIC>creative writing classes</TTHEMETOPIC>&mdash;a view diametrically opposed to that of <NAME>Earle Birney</NAME>, a member with her of the Vancouver writing group, who was sitting in the audience that day. As part of the highly regarded <ORGNAME>Vancouver Institute</ORGNAME> series, Wilson again spoke at <ORGNAME STANDARD="University of British Columbia">UBC</ORGNAME> in <DATE VALUE="1958-11-">November 1958</DATE>. Here she praised what she considered the best books written by Canadians, recognizing the <TTHEMETOPIC>work of <NAME STANDARD="Birney, Earle">Birney</NAME>, <NAME STANDARD="De la Roche, Mazo">Mazo De la Roche</NAME>, <NAME>Colin McDougall</NAME>, and <NAME>Adele Wiseman</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>. She reserved special praise for <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Morley Callaghan</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Such Is My Beloved</TITLE></TTHEMETOPIC>, <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Sinclair Ross</NAME>&apos;s <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">As for Me and My House</TITLE></TTHEMETOPIC>, and <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Robertson Davies</NAME>&apos; <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Mixture of Frailties</TITLE></TTHEMETOPIC>. However, she was quick to point out that Canadian literature as such did not in her view exist as there was no such thing as a school of <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Canadian-novel writing.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 240" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">240</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She further argued that there was no need for one to exist.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 239-41" DBREF="64285">239-41</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">A Cat among the Falcons</TITLE></HEADING><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE>December 1959</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PPERIODICALPUBLICATION>EW published in the second issue of <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Canadian Literature</TITLE> an <TGENRE GENRENAME="ESSAY"><TGENRE GENRENAME="LITERARYCRITICISM">article</TGENRE></TGENRE> titled <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">A Cat among the Falcons</TITLE>, which attacks <TTHEMETOPIC>creative writing classes</TTHEMETOPIC> and also illustrates her thoughts on <TTHEMETOPIC>literary creativity</TTHEMETOPIC> in general.</PPERIODICALPUBLICATION></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 242" DBREF="64285">242</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><PATTITUDES>The title embraces controversy and makes something witty of her habitual modesty.</PATTITUDES> In her extended argument against the value of <TTHEMETOPIC>creative writing classes</TTHEMETOPIC>, EW maintains that good writers must be self-taught and that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the conditions of privacy are the only conditions under which writing can be done.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 242" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">242</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She concedes that a writer must be taught the fine points of language and the mechanics of writing, and that it is important to read widely. However, the creative process cannot be forced. <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">Great writers like <NAME STANDARD="Shakespeare, William">Shakespeare</NAME> simply have <SOCALLED>The Gift</SOCALLED>;</TINTERTEXTUALITY> Canadian writer <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME>Sheila Watson</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC> possesses this creative <SOCALLED>gift</SOCALLED> in the form of a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">lighted mind</QUOTE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 242, 243" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">242, 243</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Finally, EW sheds light on her own formation as writer, but maintains that the process is essentially mysterious. She simply states that after the war she felt compelled to write and that she followed this compulsion.</P><RESEARCHNOTE>kgl: should this have a bibcit?</RESEARCHNOTE></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RPENALTIES>The article put great strain on her friendship with <NAME>Earle Birney</NAME>, who was fighting to keep creative writing courses alive at the <ORGNAME>University of British Columbia</ORGNAME>.</RPENALTIES> As an explanation she wrote to Birney, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I have suffered a good deal of anguish in the process of writing my short piece in <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Canadian Literature</TITLE>. . . while I think that <EMPH>personal</EMPH> help, which you have so often &amp; willingly given, is wonderful&mdash; classes . . . have increasingly disturbed me. . . . I hope you can continue to have warm friendly feelings toward me as I have to you.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 243" DBREF="64285" QTDIN="QTDINYES">243</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Birney was not persuaded by the letter and thought that EW was hard-headed and narrow-minded on this issue. He eventually wrote back countering many of her arguments and expressing disappointment that she had not sought an exchange of ideas before publishing her views. He went public with his rebuttal in a <ORGNAME>CBC</ORGNAME> broadcast in 1961.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CB Stouck 243-4" DBREF="64285">243-4</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><WORKSCITED><SOURCE>Unless otherwise noted, all information is from the FC.</SOURCE><SOURCE></SOURCE></WORKSCITED></DIV0></WRITING>